`d=256`, `k=24` including self, `K_g=64`, `H=8`, `L=2`, bf16 mixed precision on `2x80GB`.\\n/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/codex_subagents/20260328_mesh_center_wave1/proposal-attn/last_message.txt:5:Fallback ladder: exact chunked mode, pooled super-proposals, global-only mode, then full bypass to the current baseline; the report also includes a file-by-file implementation sketch for `dataset_v4.py`, `model.py`, `trainer.py`, config files, and an optional new `vae_poc/proposal_attn.py`.\\n/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/codex_subagents/20260328_mesh_center_wave1/proposal-attn/status.json:4:  \\\"agent_name\\\": \\\"proposal-attn\\\",\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.started\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_40\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc \\\"grep -RInE \\\\\\\"proposal|num_proposals|K_g|topk|global proposal|center head|attention\\\\\\\" /dev_vepfs/rc_wu/codex_subagents/20260328_mesh_center_wave1 /dev_vepfs/rc_wu/codex_subagents/20260328_mesh_center_wave2 --include='prompt.md' 2>/dev/null | sed -n '1,260p'\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"\",\"exit_code\":null,\"status\":\"in_progress\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_40\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc \\\"grep -RInE \\\\\\\"proposal|num_proposals|K_g|topk|global proposal|center head|attention\\\\\\\" /dev_vepfs/rc_wu/codex_subagents/20260328_mesh_center_wave1 /dev_vepfs/rc_wu/codex_subagents/20260328_mesh_center_wave2 --include='prompt.md' 2>/dev/null | sed -n '1,260p'\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/codex_subagents/20260328_mesh_center_wave1/scheme2-arprob/prompt.md:1:Task: Design scheme 2 for /dev_vepfs/rc_wu/armesh-dev: use s_i=[h_i,e(v0),e(v1),e(v2)] with center score head + uncertainty head, treating center as a distribution / calibrated proposal problem.\\n/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/codex_subagents/20260328_mesh_center_wave1/scheme2-arprob/prompt.md:7:- Explain how this interfaces with proposal selection and later attention.\\n/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/codex_subagents/20260328_mesh_center_wave1/proposal-attn/prompt.md:1:Task: Design the proposal attention module for /dev_vepfs/rc_wu/armesh-dev using face proposals [M,d], proposal centers [M,3], local kNN in center space, and cross-attention to K_g global latent tokens.\\n/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/codex_subagents/20260328_mesh_center_wave1/proposal-attn/prompt.md:3:Output file: /dev_vepfs/rc_wu/codex_subagents/20260328_mesh_center_wave1/proposal-attn/summary.md\\n/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/codex_subagents/20260328_mesh_center_wave1/proposal-attn/prompt.md:5:- Define exact module graph, tensor shapes, and safe defaults for M,d,k,K_g.\\n/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/codex_subagents/20260328_mesh_center_wave2/memory-guardrails/prompt.md:1:Task: Derive a memory/OOM guardrail plan for running the center head and proposal attention on 2x80GB in /dev_vepfs/rc_wu/armesh-dev.\\n/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/codex_subagents/20260328_mesh_center_wave2/memory-guardrails/prompt.md:5:- Provide concrete safe defaults and fallback ladders for N tokens, M proposals, d, k, K_g.\\n/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/codex_subagents/20260328_mesh_center_wave2/swanlab-metrics/prompt.md:1:Task: Propose the SwanLab metric schema and fair comparison dashboard layout for 4 center/attention variants in /dev_vepfs/rc_wu/armesh-dev.\\n/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/codex_subagents/20260328_mesh_center_wave2/swanlab-metrics/prompt.md:5:- Define exact metric names for train/val, center classification, proposal quality, and post-attn coordinate quality.\\n/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/codex_subagents/20260328_mesh_center_wave2/scheme4-lato/prompt.md:1:Task: Design scheme 4 for /dev_vepfs/rc_wu/armesh-dev: replace the global attention branch with latent cross-attention from latent/global tokens in a LATO-like manner, while keeping the front-end center classification head aligned with scheme 1.\\n/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/codex_subagents/20260328_mesh_center_wave2/scheme4-lato/prompt.md:6:- Explain how this differs from proposal-attn and when it should be cheaper/more stable.\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.started\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_41\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc \\\"sed -n '260,620p' /dev_vepfs/rc_wu/codex_subagents/20260328_mesh_center_wave1/proposal-attn/summary.md\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"\",\"exit_code\":null,\"status\":\"in_progress\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_41\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc \\\"sed -n '260,620p' /dev_vepfs/rc_wu/codex_subagents/20260328_mesh_center_wave1/proposal-attn/summary.md\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"### Start-up recommendation on 2x80GB\\n\\nUse:\\n\\n- `batch_size = 1` per GPU\\n- `devices = 2`, DDP\\n- `precision = bf16-mixed`\\n- `num_proposal_blocks = 2`\\n- activation checkpointing inside proposal blocks enabled\\n\\nThis is the safest starting point if the sparse U-Net remains unchanged.\\n\\n## Memory And Throughput Analysis On 2x80GB\\n\\nAssume one mesh per GPU with:\\n\\n- `M = 16384`\\n- `d = 256`\\n- `H = 8`\\n- `k = 24`\\n- `K_g = 64`\\n- bf16 activations\\n\\n### The good news\\n\\nProposal-to-global cross-attention is cheap.\\n\\n- logits size: `M * H * K_g = 16384 * 8 * 64 = 8,388,608` elements\\n- bf16 memory: about `16 MiB`\\n\\nThat is not the bottleneck.\\n\\n### The real bottleneck: local neighbor gather\\n\\nThe expensive tensor is gathered local K/V:\\n\\n- one gathered tensor: `M * k * d = 16384 * 24 * 256 = 100,663,296` elements\\n- bf16 memory per tensor: about `192 MiB`\\n- gathered `K_nbr + V_nbr`: about `384 MiB` per block before backward state\\n\\nThis means:\\n\\n- local attention is memory-bandwidth bound\\n- `k` matters more than `K_g`\\n- materializing neighbor-expanded tensors dominates the proposal module cost\\n\\n### Rough per-block overhead\\n\\nFor one proposal block at the defaults:\\n\\n- proposal activations and projections: low tens of MiB\\n- local gathered K/V: about `384 MiB`\\n- local attention logits: about `6 MiB`\\n- global attention logits: about `16 MiB`\\n- FFN hidden activation: about `32 MiB`\\n\\nForward scratch is roughly `0.45` to `0.70 GiB` depending on kernel fusion and whether relative-value tensors are materialized densely.\\n\\nBackward can easily push this to `1.0` to `1.5 GiB` per block if activations are saved normally.\\n\\nWith `num_proposal_blocks = 2`, the proposal module is still reasonable on 80GB GPUs, but only if:\\n\\n- it runs in bf16\\n- the kNN graph is reused across blocks\\n- query chunking is available as an OOM fallback\\n\\n### Why full self-attention is not acceptable\\n\\nIf proposals attended densely to all proposals:\\n\\n- logits alone would be `M * H * M = 16384 * 8 * 16384 = 2,147,483,648` elements\\n- bf16 memory just for logits would be about `4.0 GiB`\\n\\nThat excludes Q/K/V, softmax workspace, backward state, and FFN.\\n\\nSo dense proposal self-attention is a dead end here. Local kNN is the right constraint.\\n\\n### kNN construction cost\\n\\nNaive `torch.cdist(C, C)` on `M = 16384` produces:\\n\\n- `16384^2 = 268,435,456` distances\\n- about `1.0 GiB` in fp32, about `512 MiB` in bf16\\n\\nThat is too wasteful to repeat often. The design should therefore do one of:\\n\\n- precompute `knn_idx` from GT face centers in the dataset\\n- compute kNN once per forward in chunks\\n- use a dedicated kNN kernel / library\\n\\nDo not rebuild a dense pairwise distance matrix inside every proposal block.\\n\\n### Throughput expectation on 2x80GB\\n\\nThe proposal module should not be the dominant FLOP source. The current sparse encoder/decoder likely remains the main compute load. The new throughput risks are:\\n\\n1. local K/V gather bandwidth\\n2. kNN graph construction if implemented naively\\n3. extra DDP all-reduce on proposal-module parameters, which is small relative to the sparse backbone\\n\\nIn practical terms:\\n\\n- `K_g` can be increased moderately without much pain\\n- `k` cannot be increased casually\\n- more proposal blocks cost more than more global tokens\\n\\n## Stable Fallback Modes For Extreme `M` Or OOM\\n\\nUse deterministic fallback tiers. Do not rely on random emergency pruning.\\n\\n### Tier 0: normal mode\\n\\nConditions:\\n\\n- `M <= 16384`\\n\\nSettings:\\n\\n- `d = 256`\\n- `k = 24`\\n- `K_g = 64`\\n- `L = 2`\\n\\n### Tier 1: exact but chunked mode\\n\\nConditions:\\n\\n- `16384 < M <= 32768`\\n- or first OOM in normal mode\\n\\nSettings:\\n\\n- same semantics as Tier 0\\n- process proposal queries in chunks, for example `query_chunk = 4096`\\n- optionally reduce to `k = 16`, `K_g = 32`\\n\\nBehavior:\\n\\n- mathematically exact if `k` and `K_g` are unchanged\\n- lower peak memory\\n- lower throughput\\n\\nThis should be the first fallback because it preserves behavior.\\n\\n### Tier 2: pooled proposal mode\\n\\nConditions:\\n\\n- `32768 < M <= 65536`\\n- or repeated OOM in Tier 1\\n\\nSettings:\\n\\n- cluster face centers into super-proposals with voxel-grid or FPS grouping\\n- target `M_pool = min(16384, ceil(M / 4))`\\n- run proposal attention on pooled features\\n- broadcast pooled context back to member faces, then to head tokens\\n\\nBehavior:\\n\\n- approximate but stable\\n- preserves local/global structure better than arbitrary face dropping\\n\\nPooling rule recommendation:\\n\\n- mean-pool proposal features within cluster\\n- mean-pool centers within cluster\\n- keep at least one cluster per connected component if component ids are available later\\n\\n### Tier 3: global-only mode\\n\\nConditions:\\n\\n- kNN build failure\\n- persistent OOM even after chunking/pooling\\n\\nSettings:\\n\\n- skip local branch entirely\\n- keep proposal -> global cross-attention + FFN\\n- use `K_g = 16` or `32`\\n\\nBehavior:\\n\\n- complexity becomes `O(M * K_g)`\\n- weaker local edge-flow modeling\\n- still provides mesh-level conditioning and remains trainable\\n\\nThis is the most important last-resort mode because it is simple and predictable.\\n\\n### Tier 4: proposal bypass\\n\\nConditions:\\n\\n- catastrophic memory pressure\\n- debug mode\\n- checkpoint conversion compatibility\\n\\nSettings:\\n\\n- disable proposal module\\n- fall back to current `head_hidden_raw`\\n\\nBehavior:\\n\\n- exactly reproduces the current model path\\n- useful for ablations and safe rollback\\n\\n## Recommended Runtime Guards\\n\\n- Assert `d == decoder.out_channels == head.hidden_dim`.\\n- Assert `center_mask.sum() == total_faces`.\\n- Assert every face has exactly one proposal row after sorting.\\n- Log `M`, `T`, `k`, `K_g`, fallback tier, and per-block CUDA peak memory.\\n- If `M > M_cap` and pooling is disabled, fail loudly instead of silently truncating.\\n\\n## File-By-File Implementation Sketch\\n\\nThis is the minimal, low-risk edit plan if this design is implemented later.\\n\\n### `vae_poc/dataset_v4.py`\\n\\nAdd:\\n\\n- compute `face_centers = face_verts.mean(axis=1).astype(np.float32)`, shape `[num_faces, 3]`\\n- return `face_centers`\\n- optionally return precomputed `proposal_knn_idx` if CPU-side precompute is desired\\n\\nCollate changes:\\n\\n- concatenate `face_centers` in face-id order\\n- add `face_centers` to the batch dict\\n- if precomputing neighbors, offset and collate `proposal_knn_idx`\\n\\nReason:\\n\\n- proposal centers belong at the face level, not the voxel level\\n- the model should not infer them from `dist_to_centroid`\\n\\n### `vae_poc/model.py`\\n\\nAdd new modules:\\n\\n- `GlobalLatentPool`\\n- `FourierCenterEmbedding`\\n- `LocalProposalAttention`\\n- `ProposalCrossAttention`\\n- `ProposalAttentionBlock`\\n- `ProposalContextFusion`\\n\\nForward path changes:\\n\\n- keep full decoder `hidden`\\n- extract `proposal_feats_raw = hidden[center_mask]`\\n- construct `G` from encoder latent `z`\\n- run proposal blocks\\n- gather face context back onto `head_face_ids`\\n- fuse into `head_hidden_raw`\\n- pass fused `head_hidden` into existing heads\\n\\nAlso add config guards:\\n\\n- module enable flag\\n- fallback mode selection\\n- chunk size\\n- pooling thresholds\\n\\n### `vae_poc/trainer.py`\\n\\nPass through to the model:\\n\\n- `face_ids`\\n- `center_mask`\\n- `head_mask`\\n- `face_centers`\\n\\nLogging additions:\\n\\n- `num_proposals`\\n- `num_head_tokens`\\n- active fallback tier\\n- effective `k`\\n- effective `K_g`\\n- proposal-module peak memory\\n\\nLoss code can remain unchanged because outputs from the current heads keep the same shapes.\\n\\n### `vae_poc/config/dense256_v2_center_n_topk*.yaml`\\n\\nAdd a `proposal_attn` section, for example:\\n\\n```yaml\\nmodel:\\n  proposal_attn:\\n    enabled: true\\n    width: 256\\n    num_blocks: 2\\n    num_heads: 8\\n    knn_k: 24\\n    global_tokens: 64\\n    ffn_ratio: 4\\n    fourier_bands: 8\\n    layerscale_init: 1.0e-4\\n    use_checkpoint: true\\n    query_chunk_size: 4096\\n    m_cap: 16384\\n    tier1_m_cap: 32768\\n    tier2_m_cap: 65536\\n    pooled_cluster_size: 4\\n    global_only_fallback: true\\n```\\n\\nTraining defaults to pair with it:\\n\\n```yaml\\ntraining:\\n  precision: bf16-mixed\\n  batch_size: 1\\n  devices: 2\\n  strategy: ddp\\n```\\n\\n### `vae_poc/eval_checkpoint.py` and `vae_poc/decode.py`\\n\\nOnly minor plumbing is needed later:\\n\\n- load the new config section\\n- support checkpoints containing proposal-module weights\\n- keep a path to disable the module for backward compatibility\\n\\n### Optional new file: `vae_poc/proposal_attn.py`\\n\\nRecommended.\\n\\nPut all proposal-attention code in one file instead of bloating `model.py`.\\n\\nSuggested contents:\\n\\n- batched kNN helper\\n- center Fourier embedding\\n- global latent pooler\\n- local proposal attention kernel wrapper\\n- proposal block\\n- fallback controller\\n\\nThis keeps `model.py` readable.\\n\\n## Final Recommendation\\n\\nImplement the module as:\\n\\n1. one face proposal per face, extracted from the current `center_mask`\\n2. two proposal blocks of `local kNN attention -> global cross-attention -> FFN`\\n3. global tokens pooled once from the encoder latent sparse tensor\\n4. face context broadcast back onto the current top-k head tokens before the existing heads\\n\\nUse the following as the first safe training configuration on `2 x 80GB`:\\n\\n- `M_cap = 16384`\\n- `d = 256`\\n- `k = 24`\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.started\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_42\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc \\\"sed -n '1,260p' /dev_vepfs/rc_wu/codex_subagents/20260328_mesh_center_wave1/scheme1-head/summary.md\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"\",\"exit_code\":null,\"status\":\"in_progress\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_42\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc \\\"sed -n '1,260p' /dev_vepfs/rc_wu/codex_subagents/20260328_mesh_center_wave1/scheme1-head/summary.md\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"# Scheme 1: Quantized center classification head conditioned on token coordinates and 9 geometry bins\\n\\n## Recommendation\\n\\nUse a small auxiliary head that predicts a **coarse 3D center shift** for each masked head token, with:\\n\\n- input conditioning from the token voxel coordinate `[x_i, y_i, z_i]`\\n- input conditioning from the face geometry bins `[v0(3), v1(3), v2(3)] = 9 bins`\\n- output as `3 x 9` logits, one 9-way classification per axis\\n\\nThis is the lowest-risk \\\"wave 1\\\" design because it fits the current `dataset_v4 -> MeshFaceVAE -> trainer` contract, keeps the sparse backbone untouched, removes the current positive-vs-negative center imbalance, and produces a directly usable coarse proposal center for later attention.\\n\\nThe key choice is to predict a **local integer voxel shift** relative to the current head token, not an absolute center in `[0, 1]^3`:\\n\\n- per-axis shift range: `[-4, +4]` voxels\\n- encoded as `9` bins per axis\\n- target class per axis: `center_bin_axis in {0..8}`\\n\\nThat gives one coarse center cube of size `9^3` around each candidate token.\\n\\n## Why this scheme fits the current code\\n\\nCurrent active path:\\n\\n- `vae_poc/dataset_v4.py` builds dense voxel tokens and a GT-derived `head_mask`\\n- `vae_poc/model.py` runs the sparse encoder/decoder on all tokens, then runs the causal face head only on `head_mask`\\n- `vae_poc/trainer.py` computes reconstruction CE on those head tokens\\n\\nCurrent center supervision is a token-ranking problem implemented with:\\n\\n- `face_ids`\\n- `center_mask`\\n- `dist_to_centroid`\\n- grouped per-face softmax logic in `_compute_center_objective`\\n\\nScheme 1 should **not** add more GT grouping to the trainer. Instead, it should turn center prediction into a plain supervised classification task on every head token:\\n\\n- each head token gets one 3-axis center target\\n- the model predicts one 3-axis center target\\n- the trainer uses direct CE, not face-grouped scatter logic\\n\\nThat keeps the center signal inside the label tensor rather than in trainer-side GT routing.\\n\\n## Exact tensor flow\\n\\n### 1. Existing tensors\\n\\nLet:\\n\\n- `N`: total rasterized voxels after collate on one GPU\\n- `K`: `head_mask.sum()` tokens that go through the prediction heads\\n- `D = 256`: decoder output width from `cfg.model.decoder.out_channels`\\n- `B_geo = 256`: existing face-offset quantization bins\\n- `B_center = 9`: new center bins per axis\\n\\nExisting tensors in the active path:\\n\\n- `batch[\\\"coords\\\"]`: `[N, 4]`, with leading batch index\\n- `batch[\\\"feats\\\"]`: `[N, 11]`\\n- `batch[\\\"bin_indices\\\"]`: `[N, 9]`\\n- `batch[\\\"head_mask\\\"]`: `[N]`\\n- `hidden = h.feats`: `[N, D]`\\n- `head_hidden = hidden[head_mask]`: `[K, D]`\\n- `gt_bins_head = batch[\\\"bin_indices\\\"][head_mask]`: `[K, 9]`\\n\\n### 2. New dataset-side target\\n\\nFor each voxel token `i` with integer voxel coordinate `c_i = coords_i[1:4] in Z^3` and owning GT face centroid `mu_f in [0, 1]^3`, define the centroid in voxel-index units:\\n\\n```text\\nmu_vox = mu_f * grid_res - 0.5\\ndelta_vox = mu_vox - c_i\\ndelta_int = clamp(round(delta_vox), -4, +4)\\ncenter_bin = delta_int + 4\\n```\\n\\nShapes:\\n\\n- `center_delta_vox`: `[N, 3]` float32\\n- `center_delta_bins`: `[N, 3]` int64\\n- `center_delta_sat_mask`: `[N, 3]` bool, true where unclamped `round(delta_vox)` exceeded `[-4, +4]`\\n\\nInterpretation:\\n\\n- `center_delta_bins[:, 0]` predicts `dx`\\n- `center_delta_bins[:, 1]` predicts `dy`\\n- `center_delta_bins[:, 2]` predicts `dz`\\n\\nThe target is coarse on purpose. The later proposal-attention stage only needs a stable approximate center, not a final sub-voxel regression target.\\n\\n### 3. Conditioning state\\n\\nFor each head token, construct three inputs:\\n\\n- decoder feature: `h_i in R^256`\\n- coordinate token: `c_i = [x_i, y_i, z_i]`\\n- geometry bins: `b_i in {0..255}^9`\\n\\nRecommended module split:\\n\\n1. `CoordConditioner`\\n2. `CenterBinConditioner`\\n3. `QuantizedCenterHead`\\n\\n#### 3.1 CoordConditioner\\n\\nInput:\\n\\n- `coords_head = batch[\\\"coords\\\"][head_mask, 1:4].long()`: `[K, 3]`\\n\\nRecommended implementation:\\n\\n- three learned axis embeddings, one per axis, each `Embedding(grid_res, 8)`\\n- concat result: `[K, 24]`\\n- projection MLP or linear: `24 -> 32`\\n\\nOutput:\\n\\n- `coord_cond`: `[K, 32]`\\n\\nThis is better than using raw normalized coordinates directly because the target itself is an integer local voxel shift.\\n\\n#### 3.2 CenterBinConditioner\\n\\nInput:\\n\\n- `cond_bins_head`: `[K, 9]`\\n\\nRecommended implementation:\\n\\n- one shared `Embedding(num_bins=256, dim=8)` applied to all 9 positions\\n- lookup output: `[K, 9, 8]`\\n- flatten: `[K, 72]`\\n- projection linear or MLP: `72 -> 64`\\n\\nOutput:\\n\\n- `bin_cond`: `[K, 64]`\\n\\nThis uses the already-learned 9-bin face geometry as a cheap geometric hint for center placement. It is the right conditioning signal for scheme 1 because it lets the center head see the local face geometry without adding a heavy proposal network.\\n\\n#### 3.3 QuantizedCenterHead\\n\\nInput fusion:\\n\\n```text\\ncenter_in = cat([head_hidden, coord_cond, bin_cond], dim=-1)\\n```\\n\\nShape:\\n\\n- `center_in`: `[K, 352]`\\n\\nRecommended trunk:\\n\\n- `Linear(352, 128) -> SiLU`\\n- `Linear(128, 128) -> SiLU`\\n- `Linear(128, 3 * 9)`\\n\\nOutput:\\n\\n- `center_delta_logits`: `[K, 3, 9]`\\n\\nPer-axis prediction:\\n\\n- `pred_center_bins = argmax(center_delta_logits, dim=-1)`: `[K, 3]`\\n- `pred_center_shift = pred_center_bins - 4`: `[K, 3]`\\n\\nDecode to coarse center in normalized mesh coordinates:\\n\\n```text\\npred_center_xyz = (coords_head.float() + pred_center_shift.float() + 0.5) / grid_res\\n```\\n\\nShape:\\n\\n- `pred_center_xyz`: `[K, 3]`\\n\\nThis output is exactly what a later proposal module wants as a coarse proposal center.\\n\\n## Module boundaries\\n\\n### Leave unchanged\\n\\n- sparse encoder in `MeshFaceVAE.encoder`\\n- sparse decoder in `MeshFaceVAE.decoder`\\n- existing causal face reconstruction head in `CausalFaceMLP`\\n\\n### Add\\n\\n- `CoordConditioner`\\n- `CenterBinConditioner`\\n- `QuantizedCenterHead`\\n\\n### Minimal coupling rule\\n\\nDo **not** entangle the quantized center head with the sparse backbone. The clean boundary is:\\n\\n1. encoder/decoder produce `hidden`\\n2. causal face head produces or consumes 9-bin geometry tokens\\n3. center head consumes `hidden + coords + 9 bins`\\n\\nThis keeps the center design swappable and makes it easy to compare against the current binary `center_head`.\\n\\n## Train-time teacher forcing vs val/inference inputs\\n\\nThis must be explicit, otherwise the design is easy to leak.\\n\\n### Train\\n\\nTrain exactly like the current causal MLP does:\\n\\n- `head_hidden = hidden[head_mask]`\\n- `cond_bins_head = batch[\\\"bin_indices\\\"][head_mask]`\\n- the reconstruction head uses teacher forcing\\n- the center head also uses teacher-forced geometry bins\\n\\nTrain-time center loss:\\n\\n- target: `batch[\\\"center_delta_bins\\\"][head_mask]`\\n- prediction: `outputs[\\\"center_delta_logits\\\"]`\\n\\nReason:\\n\\n- the center head is conditioned on geometry\\n- during train, the cleanest and most stable conditioning source is GT 9-bin geometry\\n- this matches the current `CausalFaceMLP` convention and keeps optimization simple\\n\\n### Validation in the current ablation harness\\n\\nValidation should use **autoregressive geometry bins**, not GT bins:\\n\\n1. run the existing reconstruction head with `gt_bins=None`\\n2. compute\\n   - `pred_v0 = logits_v0.argmax(dim=-1)`\\n   - `pred_v1 = logits_v1.argmax(dim=-1)`\\n   - `pred_v2 = logits_v2.argmax(dim=-1)`\\n3. concatenate to `pred_bins_head = [K, 9]`\\n4. feed `pred_bins_head.detach()` into the center head\\n\\nSo the val center path is:\\n\\n```text\\nhidden -> causal 9-bin AR logits -> argmax 9 bins -> quantized center head\\n```\\n\\nThat is the correct no-teacher-forcing boundary for scheme 1.\\n\\n### Real inference\\n\\nReal inference should use the same center conditioning as validation:\\n\\n- no GT bins\\n- no GT center targets\\n- center head conditioned on autoregressive predicted 9 bins only\\n\\nHowever, one existing leak remains outside the center head itself:\\n\\n- current `head_mask` is built from GT centroid distance in `dataset_v4.py`\\n\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.started\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_43\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc \\\"sed -n '1,260p' /dev_vepfs/rc_wu/codex_subagents/20260328_mesh_center_wave1/proposal-attn/summary.md\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"\",\"exit_code\":null,\"status\":\"in_progress\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_43\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc \\\"sed -n '1,260p' /dev_vepfs/rc_wu/codex_subagents/20260328_mesh_center_wave1/proposal-attn/summary.md\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"# Proposal Attention Module Design\\n\\n## Scope\\n\\nDesign a face-proposal attention module for the current `vae_poc` path in `/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/armesh-dev`, using:\\n\\n- face proposals `P0` with shape `[M, d]`\\n- proposal centers `C` with shape `[M, 3]`\\n- local `k`-NN in center space\\n- cross-attention from proposals to `K_g` global latent tokens\\n\\nThis report is a design only. No repo files were modified and no experiments were run.\\n\\n## Fit To Current Code\\n\\nThe clean integration point is inside `MeshFaceVAE.forward()` after the decoder produces dense hidden features `hidden = h.feats` and before the existing `CausalFaceMLP` / topology heads run.\\n\\nThe current data path already exposes almost everything needed:\\n\\n- `hidden`: decoder features for every rasterized voxel, shape `[N, d_dec]`\\n- `center_mask`: exactly one representative voxel per face\\n- `head_mask`: top-k voxels per face already selected for the prediction heads\\n- `face_ids`: voxel-to-face ownership\\n\\nThe missing tensor is `face_centers [M, 3]`. It should be exported from `dataset_v4.py` and collated in face order so that proposal index `m` corresponds to global face id `m`.\\n\\n## Exact Module Graph\\n\\n### Symbols\\n\\n- `B`: number of meshes in the local batch on one GPU\\n- `N`: total rasterized voxels after collate on one GPU\\n- `T`: total head tokens after `head_mask` selection\\n- `M`: total faces / proposals after collate\\n- `N_z`: total encoder latent sparse sites\\n- `d`: proposal width\\n- `H`: number of attention heads\\n- `d_h = d / H`\\n- `k`: number of local neighbors, including self\\n- `K_g`: number of global latent tokens per mesh\\n\\n### Default dimensions\\n\\n- `M_cap = 16384`\\n- `d = 256`\\n- `H = 8`\\n- `d_h = 32`\\n- `k = 24`\\n- `K_g = 64`\\n- `num_proposal_blocks = 2`\\n- `ffn_ratio = 4`\\n- `dropout = 0.0`\\n- `layerscale_init = 1e-4`\\n- `dtype = bf16`\\n\\nThese defaults are chosen to fit cleanly with the current `decoder.out_channels = 256` and `head.hidden_dim = 256` in `vae_poc/config/dense256_v2_center_n_topk*.yaml`.\\n\\n### Stage 0: Proposal extraction\\n\\nStart from the current decoder output:\\n\\n- `hidden = h.feats`, shape `[N, 256]`\\n- `proposal_feats_raw = hidden[center_mask]`, shape `[M, 256]`\\n- `head_hidden_raw = hidden[head_mask]`, shape `[T, 256]`\\n- `head_face_ids = face_ids[head_mask]`, shape `[T]`\\n- `proposal_face_ids = face_ids[center_mask]`, shape `[M]`\\n\\nImplementation rule:\\n\\n- enforce `proposal_face_ids` to be unique and sorted\\n- build `face_to_proposal_idx`, shape `[M]`, so `face_to_proposal_idx[f] -> proposal row`\\n- since `dataset_v4.collate_fn_v4()` already offsets `face_ids` across samples, the simplest contract is:\\n  - `face_centers` is collated in the same global face-id order\\n  - `proposal_face_ids == torch.arange(M)` after sorting\\n\\n### Stage 1: Center positional encoding\\n\\nUse normalized mesh-space centers from the dataset:\\n\\n- `C`, shape `[M, 3]`, range approximately `[0, 1]`\\n\\nEncode centers with a lightweight Fourier MLP:\\n\\n- `center_pe = Fourier3D(C, num_bands=8)`, shape `[M, 48]`\\n- `center_proj = MLP(48 -> 128 -> 256)`, output shape `[M, 256]`\\n- `P = proposal_feats_raw + center_proj(center_pe)`, shape `[M, 256]`\\n\\nReason:\\n\\n- raw center coordinates alone are too weak\\n- full learned relative-position tables do not make sense in continuous 3D center space\\n\\n### Stage 2: Global latent token constructor\\n\\nConstruct `K_g` fixed-width global tokens from encoder latent sparse features, not from the per-face proposals.\\n\\nInputs:\\n\\n- encoder latent sparse tensor `z`\\n- `z.feats`, shape `[N_z, 32]`\\n- `z.coords[:, 1:4]`, shape `[N_z, 3]`\\n\\nProject latent memory into proposal width:\\n\\n- `z_mem = Linear(32 -> 256)(z.feats) + CoordMLP(norm(z.coords[:, 1:4]))`, shape `[N_z, 256]`\\n\\nPer-mesh learned query pooler:\\n\\n- learned query table `Q_g`, shape `[K_g, 256]`\\n- repeated per mesh: `Q_g_batch`, shape `[B, K_g, 256]`\\n\\nCross-attend queries into sparse latent memory for each mesh:\\n\\n- `G = CrossAttn(Q = Q_g_batch, K = z_mem, V = z_mem)`, shape `[B, K_g, 256]`\\n\\nThis is the only place that touches the sparse latent sites. After this, proposal blocks only see `[M, 256]` proposals and `[B, K_g, 256]` global tokens.\\n\\n### Stage 3: Local neighborhood graph\\n\\nBuild one `k`-NN graph in center space and reuse it across all proposal blocks.\\n\\nInputs:\\n\\n- `C`, shape `[M, 3]`\\n- `proposal_batch_ids`, shape `[M]`\\n\\nOutput:\\n\\n- `knn_idx`, shape `[M, k]`\\n\\nRules:\\n\\n- neighbors are restricted within each mesh\\n- index 0 should be self\\n- if a mesh has fewer than `k` proposals, repeat self to pad\\n- compute once per forward pass, never once per layer\\n\\nImportant:\\n\\n- do not build a full `[M, M]` distance matrix for large `M` unless chunked\\n- if `knn_idx` can be precomputed in the dataset from fixed GT face centers, that is even better\\n\\n### Stage 4: Proposal attention block\\n\\nUse a pre-norm residual block repeated `L = 2` times.\\n\\nFor block `l`, with input `P_l` of shape `[M, 256]`:\\n\\n#### 4.1 Local center-space attention\\n\\n- `Q = W_q(LN(P_l))`, shape `[M, H, d_h] = [M, 8, 32]`\\n- `K = W_k(LN(P_l))`, shape `[M, 8, 32]`\\n- `V = W_v(LN(P_l))`, shape `[M, 8, 32]`\\n- gather neighbors with `knn_idx`:\\n  - `K_nbr`, shape `[M, k, H, d_h]`\\n  - `V_nbr`, shape `[M, k, H, d_h]`\\n- relative offsets:\\n  - `R = C[knn_idx] - C[:, None, :]`, shape `[M, k, 3]`\\n  - `R_bias = RelMLP(3 -> 32 -> H)`, shape `[M, k, H]`\\n  - `R_val = RelMLP_v(3 -> 32 -> d)`, shape `[M, k, 256]`\\n\\nAttention:\\n\\n- `attn_local[m, h, j] = softmax_j((Q[m, h] · K_nbr[m, j, h]) / sqrt(d_h) + R_bias[m, j, h])`\\n- `O_local[m] = sum_j attn_local[m, :, j] * (V_nbr[m, j] + reshape(R_val[m, j]))`\\n- `O_local`, shape `[M, 256]`\\n\\nResidual:\\n\\n- `P_local = P_l + LayerScale_local * W_o(O_local)`\\n\\n#### 4.2 Global cross-attention\\n\\nEach proposal attends to the `K_g` global tokens from its own mesh.\\n\\n- `Qp = W_qg(LN(P_local))`, shape `[M, H, d_h]`\\n- `Kg = W_kg(G[proposal_batch_ids])`, broadcast logically from `[B, K_g, 256]`\\n- `Vg = W_vg(G[proposal_batch_ids])`\\n- `O_global = MHCA(Qp, Kg, Vg)`, shape `[M, 256]`\\n- `P_global = P_local + LayerScale_global * W_og(O_global)`\\n\\n#### 4.3 Feed-forward\\n\\n- `FFN(LN(P_global))`: `256 -> 1024 -> 256`\\n- `P_{l+1} = P_global + LayerScale_ffn * FFN(...)`\\n\\n### Stage 5: Broadcast face context back to the head tokens\\n\\nThe prediction heads still operate on the existing top-k raster tokens, not on one token per face. The proposal module provides per-face context.\\n\\n- `proposal_ctx = P_L`, shape `[M, 256]`\\n- `head_ctx = proposal_ctx[head_face_ids]`, shape `[T, 256]`\\n- `head_hidden = head_hidden_raw + W_ctx(LN(head_ctx))`, shape `[T, 256]`\\n\\nThen keep the current heads unchanged:\\n\\n- `CausalFaceMLP(head_hidden, gt_bins[head_mask])`\\n- `topo_edge_head(head_hidden)`\\n- `topo_boundary_head(head_hidden)`\\n- `center_head(head_hidden)`\\n\\nThis is the lowest-risk integration because it preserves the current output contract and loss code.\\n\\n## Tensor Shape Summary\\n\\n### Per mesh\\n\\n| Tensor | Shape | Notes |\\n|---|---:|---|\\n| proposals | `[M, 256]` | one representative token per face |\\n| centers | `[M, 3]` | face centroids in normalized mesh coordinates |\\n| global tokens | `[64, 256]` | pooled from encoder latent sparse tensor |\\n| `knn_idx` | `[M, 24]` | local neighbor list, includes self |\\n| head tokens | `[T, 256]` | existing top-k tokens used by prediction heads |\\n\\n### Local attention internals\\n\\n| Tensor | Shape |\\n|---|---:|\\n| `Q` | `[M, 8, 32]` |\\n| `K_nbr` | `[M, 24, 8, 32]` |\\n| `V_nbr` | `[M, 24, 8, 32]` |\\n| `R` | `[M, 24, 3]` |\\n| `attn_local` | `[M, 8, 24]` |\\n| `O_local` | `[M, 256]` |\\n\\n### Global cross-attention internals\\n\\n| Tensor | Shape |\\n|---|---:|\\n| proposal queries | `[M, 8, 32]` |\\n| global K/V | `[B, 64, 8, 32]` |\\n| attention logits | `[M, 8, 64]` |\\n| `O_global` | `[M, 256]` |\\n\\n## Safe Defaults For `M`, `d`, `k`, `K_g`\\n\\n### Primary defaults\\n\\n- `M_cap = 16384`\\n- `d = 256`\\n- `k = 24`\\n- `K_g = 64`\\n\\n### Why these values\\n\\n- `M_cap = 16384`\\n  - matches the current `max_faces=16000` training regime with a small margin\\n  - keeps one proposal per face, which is the cleanest semantics\\n- `d = 256`\\n  - exactly matches the current decoder output and head input width\\n  - avoids an extra proposal-to-head width conversion\\n- `k = 24`\\n  - enough local support to capture neighboring faces around loops and patch boundaries\\n  - noticeably safer than `k = 32` for gathered K/V activation size\\n- `K_g = 64`\\n  - large enough for useful mesh-level context\\n  - small enough that proposal-to-global attention is not the bottleneck\\n\\n### Start-up recommendation on 2x80GB\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n{\"type\":\"error\",\"message\":\"Reconnecting... 1/5 (stream disconnected before completion: Transport error: network error: error decoding response body)\"}\n{\"type\":\"item.started\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_44\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc \\\"sed -n '130,210p' /dev_vepfs/rc_wu/codex_subagents/20260328_mesh_center_wave1/scheme2-arprob/summary.md\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"\",\"exit_code\":null,\"status\":\"in_progress\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_44\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc \\\"sed -n '130,210p' /dev_vepfs/rc_wu/codex_subagents/20260328_mesh_center_wave1/scheme2-arprob/summary.md\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"\\n- `center_fail_auroc`: use `-log_tau2_f` or the derived face confidence to classify whether top-1 center is correct\\n- `center_aurc`: area under risk-coverage curve when sorting faces by confidence\\n- `center_dist_at_coverage_{50,75,90}`: expected center distance of the chosen token under confidence-based filtering\\n\\nThese matter more than raw loss because proposal-attention will consume only a subset of faces/proposals.\\n\\n## Proposal outputs for later attention\\n\\nScheme 2 should emit one calibrated proposal per face by default.\\n\\nPer head token, decode a token-center point from the predicted face vertices:\\n\\n- dequantize `v0/v1/v2` bins to offsets using the existing `decode.bins_to_offsets`\\n- recover the 3 face vertices per token: `[N_h, 3, 3]`\\n- define token center:\\n  `c_i = mean(vertices_i, dim=1)`: `[N_h, 3]`\\n\\nAggregate to face proposals:\\n\\n- `proposal_center_f = sum_i p(i|f) * c_i`: `[F, 3]`\\n- `proposal_feat_f = sum_i p(i|f) * W_prop(s_proj_i)`: `[F, d_prop]`\\n- recommended `d_prop = 256`\\n\\nCalibrated face confidence for proposal selection:\\n\\n- `proposal_conf_f = exp(-H(p_f)) * exp(-0.5 * clamp(log_tau2_f, -6, 3))`\\n\\nInterpretation:\\n\\n- concentrated `p_f` raises confidence\\n- high uncertainty lowers confidence\\n\\nSelection policy before later attention:\\n\\n1. Build one `(proposal_feat_f, proposal_center_f, proposal_conf_f)` per face.\\n2. Keep either:\\n   - top `M` faces by `proposal_conf_f`, or\\n   - all faces above a fixed confidence threshold chosen from the val AURC curve.\\n3. Feed only the kept proposals into the proposal-attention module.\\n\\nWhy this interfaces cleanly with the later attention design:\\n\\n- proposal-attention wants `[M, d]` features and `[M, 3]` centers\\n- scheme 2 already outputs exactly that after face-wise aggregation\\n- kNN in center space should use `proposal_center_f`\\n- the attention block can additionally append `log_tau2_f` or `proposal_conf_f` as a scalar side feature, but it does not need a full covariance model\\n\\nIf a face is very ambiguous, scheme 2 naturally spreads mass and lowers confidence instead of forcing a brittle center choice. That is the right behavior for downstream proposal pruning.\\n\\n## Compute and stability notes\\n\\n- Extra conditioning cost is small:\\n  - `s_i` grows from `256` to `448`\\n  - two tiny MLP/linear heads on `N_h` tokens and `F` pooled faces\\n- Memory cost is negligible relative to the sparse encoder/decoder\\n- Face-wise softmax/segment-reduce is the only new nontrivial op\\n- Keep `log_tau2` clipped and always include `tau_floor`, otherwise early training can blow up face-wise temperatures\\n\\n## File-by-file implementation sketch\\n\\n### `vae_poc/model.py`\\n\\n- Extend `CausalFaceMLP.forward` so it can optionally return the chosen bins and/or embeddings for `v0`, `v1`, `v2`.\\n- Add a small fusion block that builds `s_i = [h_i, e(v0), e(v1), e(v2)]`.\\n- Replace the current `center_head = BinaryHead(...)` path with:\\n  - token score head: `center_score_head`\\n  - face uncertainty head: `center_uncertainty_head`\\n- Return:\\n  - `center_score_logits`: `[N_h]`\\n  - `center_log_tau2`: `[F]`\\n  - optionally `center_token_bins_v0/v1/v2` or a packed helper output if you want proposal-center decoding inside the module\\n\\n### `vae_poc/trainer.py`\\n\\n- Replace `_compute_center_objective` with a face-wise categorical routine.\\n- Build `q(i|f)` from `dist_to_centroid`.\\n- Compute `p(i|f)` from `center_score_logits` and `center_log_tau2`.\\n- Add:\\n  - `L_soft`\\n  - `L_hard`\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n{\"type\":\"error\",\"message\":\"Reconnecting... 1/5 (stream disconnected before completion: Transport error: network error: error decoding response body)\"}\n"}}
