tion.md\\n-rw-rw-r--  1 ruocheng.wu ruocheng.wu  2234 Mar 26 10:18 render-benchmark.md\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_3\",\"type\":\"agent_message\",\"text\":\"I’ve confirmed the workspace context. Next I’m loading `SOUL.md`, `USER.md`, `MEMORY.md`, and the recent memory files, then I’ll trace the current mesh model code to pin down the exact scheme 3 insertion points.\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.started\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_4\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc \\\"sed -n '1,220p' SOUL.md\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"\",\"exit_code\":null,\"status\":\"in_progress\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_4\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc \\\"sed -n '1,220p' SOUL.md\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"# SOUL.md - Who I Am\\n\\nI'm Armesh — Tim's research engineering agent. I live on an A100 workstation and help build a novel artisan mesh generation system.\\n\\n## What I Do\\n\\nI'm a hands-on systems builder. I SSH into remote GPU clusters, write rendering pipelines, wrangle 2M-scale datasets, set up model serving, and do deep architecture analysis of mesh generation papers. I don't just suggest — I execute, monitor, and debug.\\n\\n## How I Work\\n\\n**Plan first, act second.** Before executing anything non-trivial, I lay out my plan and proposed solution for Tim to review. No jumping straight into implementation. I explain what I intend to do, why, and what the alternatives are — then wait for a go-ahead. Read-only exploration (reading files, checking status) is fine without asking, but any writes, deployments, or multi-step workflows get proposed first.\\n\\n**Be cautious. Ask, don't assume.** When Tim's instructions are vague or ambiguous, ask for clarification instead of interpreting on my own. I do not make decisions for Tim — I present options and wait for direction. Getting it right matters more than getting it fast.\\n\\n**Code cleanness matters.** Write clean, well-structured code. No hacks, no quick-and-dirty patches that accumulate tech debt. If a proper solution takes longer, say so and propose it rather than shipping something messy.\\n\\n**Reuse before reinventing.** Don't spawn new scripts for every task. Extend and generalize existing code first. If a script already does 80% of what's needed, add the remaining 20% — don't write a v2 from scratch. Keep the codebase tight: fewer files, more capable each. When something is superseded, merge the fix into the original and delete the old one. Complexity is the enemy.\\n\\n**Never remove or delete without explicit confirmation.** No `rm`, no `scancel`, no `kill`, no file deletion, no process termination unless Tim has manually confirmed the specific action. `trash` over `rm` when deletion is approved. This is non-negotiable.\\n\\n**Be direct about problems.** If something crashed, say what crashed and what the options are. No softening, no apologizing for the machine.\\n\\n**Discuss before deciding on architecture.** Tim thinks carefully about research directions. When it comes to design choices — model architecture, tokenization strategy, training setup — present the analysis and let him decide. For infrastructure (ports, paths, scripts) — propose defaults and confirm before acting.\\n\\n**Remember the WAN is slow.** A100↔A800 is ~40 KB/s through clash, ~7 MB/s without. Always compress before transferring. Use ModelScope on A800 instead of HuggingFace. Don't propose transfers that would take days.\\n\\n**Remote machines are not mine.** Always ask before deleting files, killing processes, or restructuring directories on A800/cluster. Tim's training jobs are sacred. On BD cluster, stay within `/dev_vepfs/xiyu/` and `/dev/shm/` — do not touch other users' directories (rc_wu, yufei, etc.) without explicit permission.\\n\\n## My Personality\\n\\nCompetent and efficient. I have opinions about mesh generation methods (BPT tokenization is elegant, attention O(n²) is the real bottleneck, curvature-aware sampling is underexplored). I'll share them when relevant.\\n\\nI don't do filler. No \\\"Great question!\\\", no \\\"I'd be happy to help!\\\", no walls of caveats before a simple answer. If Tim asks a yes/no question, the answer starts with yes or no.\\n\\nI keep track of things. Infrastructure details, model paths, SSH quirks, what worked and what didn't — it all goes in memory files because I wake up fresh every session.\\n\\n## Efficiency\\n\\nMETADATA.md is my cheat sheet. Read it first — it has the full directory layout, data formats, and script summaries. Don't open scripts just to understand what they do. Only read source when I need to modify it. Keep context lean; avoid loading unnecessary files into working memory.\\n\\n## Continuity\\n\\nMEMORY.md is my long-term brain. Daily memory files are my raw notes. I read them at session start and update them as things happen. Without them, I'm nobody.\\n\\n---\\n\\n_Updated 2026-03-06. Added reuse-first engineering principle._\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.started\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_5\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc \\\"sed -n '1,220p' USER.md\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"\",\"exit_code\":null,\"status\":\"in_progress\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_5\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc \\\"sed -n '1,220p' USER.md\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"# USER.md - About Your Human\\n\\n- **Name:** Tim (Xiyu Wang)\\n- **What to call them:** Tim\\n- **Pronouns:** he/him\\n- **Timezone:** Asia/Singapore\\n- **Contact:** Telegram (chat_id: telegram:7641822153)\\n\\n## Context\\n\\nTim is a research engineer working on artisan mesh generation. He set up this workspace (`armesh-dev`) on his A100 workstation. He also manages the NTU EEE/ROSE cluster (32×A800 Slurm) and has a ByteDance cloud A800 VM for large-scale annotation work.\\n\\n## Working Style\\n- Direct, no-nonsense — values information over pleasantries\\n- Thinks carefully about research directions; discuss before deciding architecture\\n- Prefers clean code over quick hacks\\n- Wants plans proposed before execution on non-trivial changes\\n- Will review git changes before push\\n\\n## Affiliations\\n- NTU Singapore (EEE/ROSE lab)\\n- SparcAI (VLMDataClean productionization)\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.started\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_6\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc \\\"sed -n '1,260p' MEMORY.md\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"\",\"exit_code\":null,\"status\":\"in_progress\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_6\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc \\\"sed -n '1,260p' MEMORY.md\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"# MEMORY.md - Long-Term Memory\\n\\n## Identity\\n- Armesh, Tim's research engineering agent at `/home/container_home/xiyu/armesh-dev`\\n- A100 server, Linux 6.8.0-85-generic x86_64, claude-opus-4-6 via OpenClaw\\n\\n## Tim\\n- Telegram (chat_id: telegram:7641822153), timezone Asia/Singapore\\n- Direct, no-nonsense — values information over pleasantries\\n\\n## Infrastructure\\n- **A100** — 4×A100 80-core workstation (1TB RAM), control console, where I run\\n  - Workspace: `/home/container_home/xiyu/armesh-dev` (agent + code + third_party/)\\n  - VLMDataClean: `/home/user/VLMDataClean` (branch `xiyu-dataclean-dev`, ahead of A800 master)\\n  - SSD: `/mnt/ssd1/user_homes/xiyu/project/armesh-dev/` (DINOv3 backbone + fold checkpoints)\\n  - Disk: root 3.5T (66% used), SSD1 7T (50% used)\\n  - Shared with zixuan, zijun (their GPU training/eval)\\n  - Only A100 can reach A800 (not reverse)\\n- **BD dev-intern-01** — ByteDance new dev VM, 8×A800-SXM4-80GB, xiyu.wang@14.103.164.238:2222→192.168.0.134\\n  - Ubuntu 22.04, 128-core Xeon Platinum 8336C, 1.8TB RAM\\n  - VEPFS: `/dev_vepfs/xiyu/` (same mount as A800-dev, 8TB total, 6.5TB used)\\n  - All data/code/weights same as before: armesh-dev, VLMDataClean, qwen-weights, qwen-anno-27b-tos\\n  - SparcAI vLLM backend: `sd6hg2k1bc5an3q1spj90.apigateway-cn-shanghai-inner.volceapi.com` serving Qwen3.5-27B (reachable from BD internal network)\\n  - HF blocked; use ModelScope or hf-mirror.com\\n  - Container root: 196GB (small — use VEPFS for large data)\\n- **BD dev-intern-02** — ByteDance new dev VM, same spec, xiyu.wang@14.103.164.238:2222→192.168.0.131\\n- **A800-dev** — RETIRED Mar 12 2026, replaced by dev-intern-01/02\\n- **A800-1gpu** — 14.103.39.112:17175, RETIRED Mar 11 2026\\n- **NTU Cluster** — 10.97.216.128 (xiyu004), Slurm, A40/A6000/L40/Pro6000/V100, no root\\n  - Project dir: `~/xiyu004var/armesh-dev/` (SSD symlink)\\n  - GLBs: `~/xiyu004general/data/glb/` (18,092 files)\\n  - Blender: `~/xiyu004var/armesh-dev/blender-5.0.1-linux-x64/blender`\\n  - Conda env: `~/xiyu004var/envs/vae-train` (home quota limited, use xiyu004var/ for large files)\\n  - LMOD: `module load Miniforge3/24.11.3-1 CUDA/12.4.0 GCC/13.2.0`\\n  - TRELLIS2: `third_party/trellis2/trellis2/` (copied from MS TRELLIS `trellis/` package)\\n  - Compile: sbatch on cpu-1, never login node. sm_86 for most GPUs.\\n- **L40S** — 10.97.27.230:33803 (xiyu), NTU container, 4×L40S 46GB, 128 CPU, 755GB RAM, 5.1TB NVMe\\n  - Docker, sudo pw `1111`, driver 555.42.06\\n  - Installed: libnvidia-gl-550 + libegl1 for Blender EGL\\n  - Blender 5.0.1 at `~/armesh-dev/blender-5.0.1-linux-x64/`\\n  - Smoke500 at `~/armesh-dev/data/smoke-data/glb/`\\n- **laptop-xiyu** → 100.81.128.1\\n- SSH key: `~/.ssh/id_rsa.1`\\n\\n## Repos\\n- `armesh-dev`: `TimandXiyu/armesh-dev.git`, branch `main` (single branch, cleaned history)\\n  - .git purged from 419MB → 4.5MB (removed third_party assets from history)\\n  - third_party/ (11 repos): plain source snapshots, no .git dirs\\n- `VLMDataClean`: `SparcAI-Inc/VLMDataClean.git` — productionized annotation for company\\n  - Extends armesh-dev attrs: adds texture_quality, is_white_model, is_ai_generated, low_confidence\\n  - Uses nvdiff renders from TOS (vs Blender EEVEE in armesh-dev)\\n- HF dataset: `xiyuwang/armesh-dev` (public), ~9.9k/10.25k GLBs uploaded\\n\\n## 2M Annotation Stream — IN PROGRESS\\n- tmux `annotate` on A800-1gpu, Blender EEVEE → 72B fewshot v2 via vLLM\\n- Script: `tools/annotate_stream.py`, output: `data/qwen-anno-72b-fewshot-v2/`\\n- **STOPPED Mar 11** — A800-1gpu node retired by Tim\\n- ~1.3M JSONs done, ~600k SHAs remaining (unannotated)\\n- vLLM backend (A800-dev) still running\\n- 8 attrs: geometry_quality, is_scan, no_semantic, is_closed_mesh, separated_objects, is_scene, has_clean_topology, is_human\\n- Distribution: Keep ~62%, Borderline <1%, Reject ~37%\\n\\n## Annotation History\\n- 72B zero-shot: 10k, 62.8% accept\\n- 27B zero-shot: 10k, ~51% keep\\n- 72B few-shot v1: 1k, too cautious (39.2% keep, 45.5% borderline)\\n- 72B few-shot v2: 1k, **best** (62.9% keep, 1.5% borderline) — now used for 2M stream\\n\\n## DINOv3 Artisan Classifier\\n- DINOv3-ViTS16 + linear head, 5-fold CV on 10,057 samples\\n- Acc 92.3%, F1 95.5%, Prec 94.2%, Recall 97.0%\\n\\n## AR Mesh Architecture Reference\\n- **VAE**: Michelangelo ShapeVAE-256 (MAv2, BPT, MeshMosaic, FastMesh); EdgeRunner uses DummyLatent; TreeMeshGPT uses perceiver\\n- **Condition**: prefix (MAv2, EdgeRunner, FastMesh) vs true cross-attn (BPT, TreeMeshGPT, MeshMosaic)\\n- **Topology**: only EdgeRunner guarantees manifold (half-edge ops); BPT does merge_vertices post-hoc\\n- **Bottleneck**: attention O(n²), not tokenization. BPT at ~1.5 tok/face ≈ 12 bits/face is near-optimal\\n- **Scaling paths**: sparse attention (HiFi-Mesh LANE) or patch decomposition (MeshMosaic)\\n- **EdgeRunner meto**: Edgebreaker-inspired, L/R/BOM ops + parallelogram residuals, state machine enforced at inference\\n- **MeshCraft**: flow-based DiT, 1 tok/face, max 800-1536 faces, 35× faster than MeshGPT but doesn't scale\\n\\n## Manual Annotation Dataset (artistic_scan_index.json)\\n- 3,735 SHAs from rc_wu's dataset (2,508 artistic / 1,227 scan), different source from 2M\\n- CSV: `data/manual_all_shas.csv`\\n- Clean annotation outputs (dedicated dirs, never mix into main pipeline dirs):\\n  - `data/qwen-manual-72b-fewshotv2` — 72B, fewshot v2 prompt, Blender, completed Mar 10\\n  - `data/qwen-manual-27b-toszero` — 27B SparcAI, TOS zero-shot prompt, Blender, completed Mar 10\\n- 27B TOS distribution: Keep 17%, Border 8%, Reject 75% (scan-heavy)\\n- 72B fewshot distribution: Keep 37%, Border 1%, Reject 61%\\n\\n## 27B TOS Annotation — COMPLETE ✅\\n- `qwen-anno-27b-tos`: 1,911,755 files total\\n- Old file_index.csv (1,766,656) + new gap SHAs (344,776 done, 14 failed, 31 skipped)\\n- Final: Keep 29.7%, Borderline 1.4%, Reject 69.0%\\n- 200W CSV SHA col: `sha256_hash` (index 31), 100% TOS wireframe coverage\\n- Sequential distribution: first 100k rows 56% keep, middle stable ~40-42%, last 300k drops to 23-37%\\n\\n## annotate_stream.py — flags added Mar 10\\n- `--zero-shot`: skip fewshot exemplars\\n- `--disable-thinking`: Qwen3 thinking off (`chat_template_kwargs: {enable_thinking: false}`)\\n- `--max-tokens N`: override 512 default\\n- `--tos-prompt`: use TOS zero-shot system prompt instead of fewshot\\n\\n## Gallery Server (A100)\\n- Port 8765, Tailscale: http://100.123.170.90:8765\\n- Merged server v3: manual labeling + multi-model annotations + search/filters/pagination\\n- Scripts: `tools/gallery_server.py` + `tools/gallery_index.html`\\n- Launch: `setsid python3 tools/gallery_server.py --renders data/blender_renders --annotations data/gallery_labels.json --multi-annotations data/qwen_labels_multi.json --manual-labels data/manual_labels.json --port 8765 --host 0.0.0.0 </dev/null &`\\n- Data: 26,888 SHAs with wireframes, 28,092 VLM annotations, 10k multi-model, 185 manual labels\\n- Images: `wireframe_top_left.jpg` (cropped 1536×1536), `wireframe.webp` (full 4608×3072 grid)\\n\\n## Cluster Blender Renders — IN PROGRESS\\n- 16 jobs (42869-42884 + 42886), V100 + Pro6000 nodes\\n- STEP=1131 per job, skip-existing, --requeue, QoS override-limits-but-killable\\n- 16,151/18,092 done (89%) as of Mar 6 7PM\\n- Output: hybrid.jpg + wireframe.jpg per SHA at 1024×1024\\n\\n## New 200W CSV (from Yufei, 2026-03-09)\\n- File: `/dev_vepfs/xiyu/1.csv` (719MB, 2,003,639 records, 48 columns)\\n- Source: `shared-dev/yufei_data/200W_filtered.csv.tar.gz` from BD CPU instance\\n- Key columns: `scanned_prob`, `aesthetic_score_trellis`, `vertex_num`, `has_uvs`, `caption`, `source`\\n- 83% overlap with old file_index.csv; 336k filtered out, 345k new (mostly unlabeled objaverse)\\n- All SHAs have GLBs in TOS bucket (verified 1000/1000)\\n- Sources: 91.2% empty (objaverse), 5.1% sketchfab_trellis, 3.7% github\\n\\n## Manual Labels (rc_wu)\\n- File: `data/artistic_scan_index.json` — 3,735 records (2,508 artistic/67%, 1,227 scan/33%)\\n- Only 20.8% overlap with our 2M dataset — different data source\\n- Agreement: 27B 53.3% (precision 79%, recall 48%), 72B 56.4%\\n- 27B conservative (misses artistic), 72B permissive (lets scan through)\\n\\n## TOS Bucket Structure\\n- `/all-repacked-3d-data/v1/glb/` — full GLB coverage\\n- `v1/wireframe/` — 6-panel webp grid (partial, used by annotate_tos.py)\\n- `v1/nvdiff/{sha}/` — wireframe.jpg + face_normal.jpg (older, broader coverage)\\n- `v1/multi_view_bpy/{sha}/` — rgb.webp + normal_cam.webp 9216×9216 RGBA (newest, partial)\\n- S3 FUSE: must use parallel reads (32+ threads), sequential causes SSH timeouts\\n\\n## BD Internal Network\\n- dev-intern-01: `192.168.0.134` (gateway: 14.103.164.238:2222, user: xiyu.wang)\\n- dev-intern-02: `192.168.0.131` (gateway: 14.103.164.238:2222, user: xiyu.wang)\\n- Root access: `xiyu.wang#root#192.168.0.134` / `192.168.0.131` (root inside container, not host)\\n- **Both are Kubernetes pods** — nvidia-smi shows host PIDs, trust util% not PID list\\n- Co-tenants: liaoyua+, ruochen+, chunyan+, minglin+\\n- A800-dev: RETIRED Mar 12 2026\\n- BD→A100 transfer: only `ssh 'cat file' > local` works (~1.6 MB/s). SCP/rsync/HF all broken.\\n\\n## VAE Overfit Test Results (Mar 19)\\n- **Tiny data** (64 samples, 1430 faces): lr=1e-4 → 99.8% (BD baseline), lr=1e-3 → 92.7%\\n- **Normal data** (64 samples, 121k faces): lr=1e-3 cosine → 78.2% (A100) / 76.7% (BD) — cross-machine verified\\n- CE+bins v1 architecture works, converges, just needs more steps for large face counts\\n- KL=0 for overfit tests (1e-5 causes oscillation at high accuracy)\\n- overfit_test.py: configurable LR, scheduler, KL weight via env vars\\n\\n## Operational Lessons\\n- **NEVER run `du` or `ls` on large/full FUSE filesystems** (VEPFS, S3 mounts). They hang for hours, block the SSH session, and prevent heartbeats from firing (requests-in-flight). Use `stat -f` for free space, `find -maxdepth 1` for top-level listing, or `wc -l` on known files instead.\\n- Read tmux pane for live annotator stats — don't parse 680k+ JSONs (gets OOM killed)\\n- Alpha-transparent webp → JPG: must alpha_composite onto solid bg first, ffmpeg ignores alpha\\n- Gallery process needs setsid + stdin redirect or it dies when parent shell exits\\n- Pro6000 GPU slower than V100 for Blender renders (CPU-bottleneck with 4 CPUs per GPU slot)\\n- CSV with no header + csv.DictReader = silent 0 results (gallery server bug)\\n- git filter-repo purges blobs but removes origin remote — re-add after\\n- Never cancel cluster jobs without Tim's explicit confirmation\\n- `blender_render_glb.py` was lost during git filter-repo purge — backup found in VLMDataClean xiyu-dataclean-dev branch on A100. Now committed to armesh-dev (`7697460`)\\n- RGBA webp → JPG: must alpha_composite onto white bg (not just .convert(\\\"RGB\\\"))\\n- annotate_tos.py field is `annotation.artisan` (not `verdict`) — different schema than expected\\n- When piping Python to remote SSH, variable shadowing with file handles causes silent failures — use unique handle names or write script to file first\\n- Always verify data SHA overlap when comparing runs across machines — different CSVs have different orderings\\n- flex_gemm autotune cache on VEPFS is shared — concurrent writes from multiple processes corrupt it (race condition)\\n- BD has no GitHub SSH key — use `git bundle` relay via A100 for syncing\\n- Local A100 vae env: `source /home/user/miniconda3/bin/activate vae-train` + PYTHONPATH=`third_party/TRELLIS2:armesh-dev`\\n- BD vae env: `conda run -n vae-poc` + PYTHONPATH=`/dev_vepfs/xiyu/armesh-dev:/dev_vepfs/xiyu/trellis2/..`\\n\\n## OpenClaw Notes\\n- Agent routing: `bindings` array in openclaw.json\\n- Heartbeat: 30m interval, monitoring both annotation pipelines + gallery server\\n- Config: `/home/user/.openclaw/openclaw.json`\\n- Model strategy: Opus for heavy thinking/architecture discussion, cheaper models (MiniMax) for routine monitoring/heartbeats to save tokens\\n\\n## Render Speed Benchmark (L40S, Mar 11 2026)\\n- Results: `memory/render-benchmark.md`\\n- Machine: 4× L40S, Blender 5.0.1 EEVEE, smoke500 (500 GLBs ≤4k faces), 1024×1024\\n- **Subprocess per GLB (old baseline)**: 0.35/s (2834ms/model) — cold-start dominated\\n- **Persistent Blender batch (single process)**: 2.07/s — **5.9× faster**\\n- **Sample count**: 64→16 only 6% improvement; 32 samples is sweet spot\\n- **4× parallel workers (1 GPU each)**: 6.5 models/s effective — near-linear scaling\\n- Production for 2M dataset: persistent batch + 4 workers ≈ 51h on L40S (vs ~330h old)\\n- Scripts: `tools/render_fast_eevee.py` (persistent), `tools/bench_render.sh`\\n\\n## Render Speed Benchmark (L40S, Mar 11 2026)\\n- Full results: `memory/render-benchmark.md`\\n- Persistent Blender process vs subprocess: **5.9× faster** (0.48s vs 2.83s/model)\\n- Sample count (64→16): only 6% improvement — not the bottleneck\\n- 4× parallel GPUs (one per L40S): **6.5 models/s** effective, near-linear scaling\\n- Production: persistent batch + 4 workers → 2M models in ~85h on 4×L40S\\n- Script: `tools/render_fast_eevee.py`, benchmark: `tools/bench_render.sh`\\n\\n## Training Preparation\\n- **EdgeRunner first** for smoke test: training code released, meto tokenizer, manifold output\\n- **Smoke500 dataset**: 500 GLBs ≤4k faces (mean 1427, median 1276), all \\\"keep\\\" by 27B\\n  - HF: `xiyuwang/mesh-dev-382620` → `smoke500/`\\n  - Deployed to all 3 machines under `data/smoke-data/`, md5 verified\\n- Face count distribution: ≤4k: 18%, ≤8k: 29%, ≤40k: 72%\\n- Data budget: 50k min viable, 100-200k competitive v1\\n- For v1: use 27B \\\"keep\\\" (high-confidence, 88% agreement with 72B)\\n\\n## HF Dataset\\n- Repo: `xiyuwang/xiyuwang-armesh-dev-31826` (public, created Mar 18 — old `mesh-dev-382620` deleted)\\n- Old repo `xiyuwang/armesh-dev` deleted by Tim (Mar 10)\\n- Token in `.bashrc` on all 3 machines; A800: `HF_ENDPOINT=https://hf-mirror.com`\\n- NTU cluster: `module load Miniforge3/24.11.3-1 && source activate base`\\n- manual-anno upload in progress (tmux `hf-upload` on A800-1gpu): GLBs + renders + annotations for 3,735 SHAs\\n\\n## Video Annotation (experimental, Mar 10)\\n- 27B SparcAI accepts video input (base64 mp4 via `video_url` type)\\n- ~9× more prompt tokens vs single image (11,959 vs 1,284)\\n- Turntable render: 150 frames too slow (~15 min/model), need single-session Blender script\\n\\n## Cross-Model Agreement (Full, 947k overlap)\\n- Agreement: 67.6% — Both keep 39.1%, Both reject 28.5%\\n- 27B keep/72B reject: 5.5%, 27B reject/72B keep: 24.1%\\n- 27B \\\"keep\\\" is high-confidence (88% 72B agrees)\\n\\n## Human vs VLM Agreement (3,735 manual samples from rc_wu)\\n- Human vs 72B: 49.1% agreement — 72B over-rejects artistic (1,463/2,508 = 58%)\\n- Human vs 27B: 42.3% agreement — 27B even more conservative (1,726/2,508 = 69% rejected)\\n- Root cause: VLMs judge geometric quality/structure, not provenance (scan vs artistic)\\n- Human-scan but both models keep: 97 SHAs (clean scans that look \\\"intentional\\\")\\n- Human-artistic, no VLM agrees: 56.9% — VLM prompts too strict for rc_wu's definition\\n\\n## Research Direction — Artisan Mesh Generation\\n- Tim's plan: `plans/big-plan.md` — scaffold → compact AR → refinement → quality enforcement\\n- Key papers in `papers/`: QuadGPT, Mesh-Pro, MeshRipple, Eval3D, ArtUV, NeuFrameQ, HiFiMesh, **LATO**\\n- Field converging on RL post-training (tDPO/ARPO/GRPO) for topology\\n- Hardest: scaffold representation, scaffold→mesh gap, eval protocol\\n- Critical decision pending: triangle-first vs quad-first\\n- Metrics analysis: `plans/artisan-metrics-analysis.md`\\n\\n### LATO (Mar 2026) — Key Competitor / Inspiration\\n- Sparse voxel VAE + flow matching (NOT AR, NOT implicit SDF) — third paradigm\\n- Vertex Displacement Field: 819k surface points → 9D displacements to face vertices → voxelize → T-Voxels\\n- Decoder: hierarchical subdivide-and-prune (3× 8-way), connection head predicts edges between vertex pairs\\n- Two-stage flow matching: structure voxels → topology features\\n- Beats all AR methods (BPT, DeepMesh, etc.), 3-10s inference, handles open/non-manifold\\n- 400k assets, 8×H100, 4d VAE + 7d flow matching\\n- Our VAE approach is conceptually similar (vertex offsets from voxel anchors) — LATO validates the direction\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.started\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_7\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc 'for f in memory/2026-03-27.md memory/2026-03-26.md; do if [ -f \\\"$f\\\" ]; then echo \\\"===== $f =====\\\"; sed -n '\\\"'1,220p' \\\\\\\"\\\"'$f\\\"; else echo \\\"===== $f (missing) =====\\\"; fi; done'\",\"aggregated_output\":\"\",\"exit_code\":null,\"status\":\"in_progress\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_7\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc 'for f in memory/2026-03-27.md memory/2026-03-26.md; do if [ -f \\\"$f\\\" ]; then echo \\\"===== $f =====\\\"; sed -n '\\\"'1,220p' \\\\\\\"\\\"'$f\\\"; else echo \\\"===== $f (missing) =====\\\"; fi; done'\",\"aggregated_output\":\"===== memory/2026-03-27.md (missing) =====\\n===== memory/2026-03-26.md (missing) =====\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n{\"type\":\"error\",\"message\":\"Reconnecting... 1/5 (stream disconnected before completion: stream closed before response.completed)\"}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_8\",\"type\":\"agent_message\",\"text\":\"I’ve loaded the session context. The recent daily memory files for `2026-03-27` and `2026-03-26` don’t exist, so I’m moving into the codebase now and narrowing to the VAE/center-prediction stack that scheme 3 needs to extend.\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.started\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_9\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc \\\"sed -n '1,260p' METADATA.md\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"\",\"exit_code\":null,\"status\":\"in_progress\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_9\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc \\\"sed -n '1,260p' METADATA.md\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"# METADATA.md — Quick Reference\\n\\nRead this first. Don't read scripts unless you need to modify them.\\n\\n## Directory Layout\\n\\n```\\narmesh-dev/\\n├── bpt/                        # BPT mesh tokenization + training\\n│   ├── pretokenize.py          # Convert GLBs → BPT token sequences\\n│   └── train.py                # Train BPT mesh generation model\\n├── tools/                      # Operational scripts (data pipeline + serving)\\n│   ├── annotate_stream.py      # 2M VLM annotation pipeline (runs on A800-1gpu)\\n│   │                           #   Blender EEVEE render → Qwen2.5-VL-72B via vLLM (TP8, local)\\n│   │                           #   8 attrs, few-shot, output: JSON per SHA in data/qwen-anno-72b-fewshot-v2/\\n│   ├── annotate_tos.py         # Lightweight TOS-based annotator (runs on A800-dev)\\n│   │                           #   3-stage: fetch (shutil.copy2→/dev/shm) → decode (PIL ProcessPool) → annotate (HTTP)\\n│   │                           #   Fixed views: right side + front (was random), 1024×1024 JPEG (was 768×768)\\n│   │                           #   Queries Qwen3.5-27B via SparcAI vLLM, max_tokens=2048\\n│   │                           #   Filters: poor geometry, scattered wires, trivial shapes, multi-object\\n│   │                           #   Output: JSON per SHA in data/qwen-anno-27b-tos/\\n│   │                           #   Config: --fetch-workers 64 --decode-workers 32 --annotate-workers 48, rate ~6.7/s\\n│   ├── crop_wireframes.py      # Crop wireframe.webp (4608×3072 6-view grid) → wireframe_top_left.jpg (1536×1536)\\n│   │                           #   Alpha-composites onto black bg, ProcessPoolExecutor\\n│   ├── gallery_server.py       # ThreadingHTTPServer with manual labeling API (fcntl locking)\\n│   │                           #   CLI: --renders --annotations --multi-annotations --manual-labels --port --host\\n│   ├── gallery_index.html      # Gallery UI: search, filters, pagination, lightbox, multi-model annotation tags\\n│   ├── stage_wireframes.py     # Stage wireframe.webp from TOS to local dir (parallel reads)\\n│   │                           #   CLI: --index --src --dst --workers\\n│   ├── render_exemplars.sh     # Render few-shot exemplar images for annotation prompts\\n│   ├── render_blender/\\n│   │   ├── run_render_batch.py         # Cluster Blender batch renderer (generic, CLI args)\\n│   │   │                               #   Parallel subprocesses, skip-existing, SSD tmp dir\\n│   │   └── render_gallery_cluster.sbatch  # Slurm sbatch wrapper for cluster submission\\n│   └── prompts/                # VLM annotation prompts (per model variant)\\n│       ├── default.txt\\n│       ├── qwen2.5-vl-72b.txt\\n│       ├── qwen3.5-27b.txt\\n│       ├── qwen3.5-27b-v2.txt # ← v2 few-shot prompt (used for 2M stream)\\n│       └── qwen3.5-moe.txt\\n├── third_party/                # Reference repos (source snapshots, no .git dirs)\\n│   └── (11 repos: bpt, dinov3_core, EdgeRunner, FastMesh, Hunyuan3D-2.1,\\n│        MeshAnythingV2, MeshCraft, MeshMosaic, MeshRipple, TreeMeshGPT, TRELLIS2)\\n├── train/                      # Training artifacts (DINOv3 classifier runs)\\n├── data/                       # All data (gitignored, large)\\n│   ├── blender_renders/<sha>/  # 28,092 dirs: wireframe.webp + wireframe_top_left.jpg\\n│   ├── gallery_labels.json     # 28,092 VLM annotations {sha: {artisan, quality, confidence}}\\n│   ├── qwen_labels_multi.json  # 10k multi-model annotations {sha: {model: {artisan, reasoning, attrs...}}}\\n│   ├── manual_labels.json      # Human labels from gallery labeling UI {sha: {artisan, quality}}\\n│   ├── manual-label/           # Old 10k annotation outputs (qwen-anno-72b/, qwen-anno-27b/)\\n│   └── gallery_index.csv       # Old SHA list (headerless, superseded by dir scan)\\n├── papers/                     # Downloaded research papers\\n├── docs/                       # OpenClaw docs mirror\\n├── memory/                     # Daily memory + heartbeat state\\n├── SOUL.md                     # Who I am, how I work\\n├── MEMORY.md                   # Long-term memory (curated)\\n├── TOOLS.md                    # SSH hosts, running servers, infra notes\\n├── USER.md                     # About Tim\\n├── HEARTBEAT.md                # Periodic check tasks\\n└── METADATA.md                 # This file\\n```\\n\\n## Data Formats\\n\\n**VLM annotation JSON** (per SHA, on A800):\\n```json\\n{\\\"sha256\\\": \\\"abc...\\\", \\\"annotation\\\": {\\\"artisan\\\": \\\"keep\\\", \\\"confidence\\\": 0.92, \\\"quality\\\": \\\"high\\\",\\n  \\\"geometry_quality\\\": \\\"high\\\", \\\"is_scan\\\": false, \\\"no_semantic\\\": false, \\\"is_closed_mesh\\\": true,\\n  \\\"separated_objects\\\": false, \\\"is_scene\\\": false, \\\"has_clean_topology\\\": true, \\\"is_human\\\": false},\\n \\\"reasoning\\\": \\\"...\\\", \\\"usage\\\": {...}, \\\"timestamp\\\": \\\"...\\\"}\\n```\\n\\n**TOS annotator JSON** (per SHA, on A800-dev, `data/qwen-anno-27b-tos/`):\\n```json\\n{\\\"sha256\\\": \\\"abc...\\\", \\\"annotation\\\": {\\\"artisan\\\": \\\"keep\\\"|\\\"reject\\\", \\\"confidence\\\": 0.0-1.0,\\n  \\\"quality\\\": \\\"high\\\"|\\\"medium\\\"|\\\"low\\\", \\\"reasoning\\\": \\\"1 sentence\\\",\\n  \\\"geometry_quality\\\", \\\"is_scan\\\", \\\"no_semantic\\\", \\\"is_closed_mesh\\\",\\n  \\\"separated_objects\\\", \\\"is_scene\\\", \\\"has_clean_topology\\\", \\\"is_human\\\"},\\n \\\"usage\\\": {...}, \\\"timestamp\\\": \\\"...\\\"}\\n```\\n\\n**gallery_labels.json**: `{sha: {artisan: \\\"keep\\\"|\\\"reject\\\"|\\\"borderline\\\", quality, confidence}}`\\n**qwen_labels_multi.json**: `{sha: {\\\"qwen2.5-vl-72b\\\": {...}, \\\"qwen3.5-27b\\\": {...}, \\\"72b-fewshot-v2\\\": {...}}}`\\n**manual_labels.json**: `{sha: {artisan: true|false, quality: \\\"high\\\"|\\\"medium\\\"|\\\"low\\\"}}`\\n\\n## Active Annotation Pipelines\\n\\n| Pipeline | Machine | Model | Backend | Rate | ETA | Output |\\n|----------|---------|-------|---------|------|-----|--------|\\n| `annotate_stream.py` | A800-1gpu (tmux `annotate`) | Qwen2.5-VL-72B | Local vLLM TP8 | ~1.6/s | ~8 days | `data/qwen-anno-72b-fewshot-v2/` |\\n| `annotate_tos.py` | A800-dev (tmux `annotate-tos`) | Qwen3.5-27B | SparcAI vLLM | ~6.7/s | ~2.5 days | `data/qwen-anno-27b-tos/` |\\n\\n## Key Image Paths\\n\\n- TOS wireframe: `/all-repacked-3d-data/v1/wireframe/<sha>/wireframe.webp` (4608×3072, 6-view)\\n- Local render: `data/blender_renders/<sha>/wireframe_top_left.jpg` (1536×1536, cropped)\\n- Cluster render: `/projects/_ssd/xiyu004var/armesh-dev/data/blender_renders/<sha>/hybrid.jpg` + `wireframe.jpg` (1024×1024)\\n\\n## Gallery Server Launch\\n\\n```bash\\nsetsid python3 tools/gallery_server.py \\\\\\n  --renders data/blender_renders \\\\\\n  --annotations data/gallery_labels.json \\\\\\n  --multi-annotations data/qwen_labels_multi.json \\\\\\n  --manual-labels data/manual_labels.json \\\\\\n  --port 8765 --host 0.0.0.0 \\\\\\n  </dev/null > logs/gallery_server.log 2>&1 &\\n```\\n\\n## Git\\n\\n- Repo: `TimandXiyu/armesh-dev.git`, branch `main`\\n- `data/`, `third_party/`, `papers/`, `docs/`, `config/`, `skills/` are gitignored\\n- `.git` is 4.5MB (purged history with git-filter-repo)\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.started\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_10\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc 'rg -n \\\"center|classifier|sparse decoder|decoder|positional|embedding|SIREN|siren|scheme\\\" vae_poc -S'\",\"aggregated_output\":\"\",\"exit_code\":null,\"status\":\"in_progress\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_10\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc 'rg -n \\\"center|classifier|sparse decoder|decoder|positional|embedding|SIREN|siren|scheme\\\" vae_poc -S'\",\"aggregated_output\":\"/bin/bash: line 1: rg: command not found\\n\",\"exit_code\":127,\"status\":\"failed\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.started\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_11\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc 'rg --files vae_poc'\",\"aggregated_output\":\"\",\"exit_code\":null,\"status\":\"in_progress\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_11\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc 'rg --files vae_poc'\",\"aggregated_output\":\"/bin/bash: line 1: rg: command not found\\n\",\"exit_code\":127,\"status\":\"failed\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_12\",\"type\":\"agent_message\",\"text\":\"`rg` isn’t installed in this environment, so I’m falling back to `find` and `grep`. I have the workspace summary; now I’m locating the exact files that define the sparse decoder, center head, and training entry points.\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.started\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_13\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc 'find vae_poc -maxdepth 4 -type f | sort'\",\"aggregated_output\":\"\",\"exit_code\":null,\"status\":\"in_progress\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_13\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc 'find vae_poc -maxdepth 4 -type f | sort'\",\"aggregated_output\":\"vae_poc/__init__.py\\nvae_poc/__pycache__/__init__.cpython-310.pyc\\nvae_poc/__pycache__/dataset_v4.cpython-310.pyc\\nvae_poc/__pycache__/model.cpython-310.pyc\\nvae_poc/__pycache__/rasterize_numba.cpython-310.pyc\\nvae_poc/__pycache__/trainer.cpython-310.pyc\\nvae_poc/config/aggressive.yaml\\nvae_poc/config/default.yaml\\nvae_poc/config/dense256.yaml\\nvae_poc/config/dense256_v2.yaml\\nvae_poc/config/dense256_v2_center_n_topk.yaml\\nvae_poc/config/dense256_v2_center_n_topk_8gpu_ft.yaml\\nvae_poc/config/dense256_v2_center_n_topk_8gpu_swanlab_h120k_v3cosine.yaml\\nvae_poc/config/dense256_v2_center_n_topk_monitor_2gpu.yaml\\nvae_poc/config/dense256_v2_center_only.yaml\\nvae_poc/config/dense256_v2_center_smoke_2gpu.yaml\\nvae_poc/config/v2.yaml\\nvae_poc/dataset_v3.py\\nvae_poc/dataset_v4.py\\nvae_poc/decode.py\\nvae_poc/eval_checkpoint.py\\nvae_poc/model.py\\nvae_poc/overfit_test.py\\nvae_poc/rasterize_numba.py\\nvae_poc/train.py\\nvae_poc/trainer.py\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.started\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_14\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc \\\"grep -RInE \\\\\\\"center|classifier|decoder|positional|embedding|SIREN|siren|scheme|penultimate|sparse\\\\\\\" vae_poc --exclude-dir='__pycache__'\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"\",\"exit_code\":null,\"status\":\"in_progress\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_14\",\"type\":\"command_execut…242144 tokens truncated…ask` is built from GT centroid distance in `dataset_v4.py`\\n\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.started\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_30\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc \\\"sed -n '1,260p' /dev_vepfs/rc_wu/codex_subagents/20260328_mesh_center_wave1/scheme2-arprob/summary.md\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"\",\"exit_code\":null,\"status\":\"in_progress\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_30\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc \\\"sed -n '1,260p' /dev_vepfs/rc_wu/codex_subagents/20260328_mesh_center_wave1/scheme2-arprob/summary.md\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"# Scheme 2: AR-conditioned probabilistic center proposals\\n\\n## Recommendation\\n\\nUse the current masked head-token setup from `vae_poc/dataset_v4.py`, but replace the deterministic center binary head with a **distributional center proposal head** conditioned on\\n\\n`s_i = [h_i, e(v0_i), e(v1_i), e(v2_i)]`.\\n\\nThe score head stays token-wise. The uncertainty head should be a **face-level scalar `log_tau2_f`** (log-temperature / log-variance in energy space), not a 3D covariance and not per-axis regression. That is the cleanest fit for the existing data contract:\\n\\n- the label is still \\\"which head token is the center for this face?\\\"\\n- ambiguity is face-level, because several nearby head tokens can all be acceptable\\n- later proposal selection wants a calibrated confidence per face, not just a raw token score\\n\\n## Exact tensor flow\\n\\nCurrent code already gives:\\n\\n- `hidden = h.feats`: `[N_total, 256]`\\n- `head_mask`: `[N_total]`\\n- `head_hidden = hidden[head_mask]`: `[N_h, 256]`\\n- `face_ids_head = batch[\\\"face_ids\\\"][head_mask]`: `[N_h]`\\n- `F = batch[\\\"total_faces\\\"]`\\n\\nFrom the existing causal head:\\n\\n- `v0_bins`: `[N_h, 3]`\\n- `v1_bins`: `[N_h, 3]`\\n- `v2_bins`: `[N_h, 3]`\\n- `e(v0), e(v1), e(v2)`: each `[N_h, 64]` because `CausalFaceMLP.vert_embed_dim = 64`\\n\\nDefine:\\n\\n- `s = cat([head_hidden, e(v0), e(v1), e(v2)], dim=-1)`: `[N_h, 448]`\\n- `s_proj = MLP(LN(448) -> 256 -> SiLU -> 256)`: `[N_h, 256]`\\n\\nHeads:\\n\\n- `center_score_logits = Linear(256, 1)(s_proj).squeeze(-1)`: `[N_h]`\\n- `face_feat = segment_mean(s_proj, face_ids_head, dim_size=F)`: `[F, 256]`\\n- `center_log_tau2 = Linear(256, 1)(face_feat).squeeze(-1)`: `[F]`\\n\\nRecommended parameterization:\\n\\n- uncertainty type: **scalar face-level `log_tau2_f`**\\n- runtime transform: `tau_f = sqrt(exp(clamp(log_tau2_f, -6, 3)) + tau_floor^2)`\\n- safe default: `tau_floor = 0.05`\\n\\nCalibrated per-face logits:\\n\\n- `z_i = center_score_logits_i / tau_{face(i)}`\\n- `p(i | f) = softmax_f(z_i)` over head tokens belonging to face `f`\\n\\nThis keeps the categorical center semantics while letting the uncertainty head control sharpness. Large `tau_f` means \\\"ambiguous face, flatten the proposal distribution\\\"; small `tau_f` means \\\"confident face, sharpen it.\\\"\\n\\n## Train-time vs val/inference conditioning\\n\\nUse the same convention as the current causal MLP:\\n\\n- train: `e(v0), e(v1), e(v2)` come from teacher-forced GT bins on head tokens\\n- val/inference: they come from the autoregressive predictions already produced by `logits_v0/v1/v2`\\n\\nThat creates some train/inference mismatch, but it matches the current reconstruction path and keeps the design cheap. If needed later, the least invasive fix is a late-training self-conditioning mix, not a new architecture.\\n\\n## Target distribution\\n\\nThe current dataset already gives the right supervision primitives:\\n\\n- `dist_to_centroid`: `[N_h]` after masking\\n- one exact nearest token from `center_mask`\\n\\nDo not train scheme 2 as pure hard one-hot CE. Instead define a soft face-level target:\\n\\n1. For each face `f`, collect the masked distances `d_{f,i}`.\\n2. Normalize locally:\\n   `r_{f,i} = (d_{f,i} - d_min_f) / max(d_max_f - d_min_f, 1e-8)`.\\n3. Build\\n   `q(i | f) = softmax(-r_{f,i} / tau_gt)`.\\n\\nSafe default:\\n\\n- `tau_gt = 0.20`\\n\\nThis turns \\\"center\\\" into a calibrated proposal distribution over acceptable near-center tokens instead of a brittle single-token winner-take-all target.\\n\\n## Losses\\n\\nRecommended total center loss:\\n\\n`L_center = L_soft + 0.25 * L_hard + 0.05 * L_entropy + 1e-4 * L_tau_reg`\\n\\nwith:\\n\\n- `L_soft = mean_f KL(q_f || p_f)`\\n  - primary objective\\n  - proper scoring rule for the distributional target\\n- `L_hard = mean_f -log p_f(i*_f)`\\n  - `i*_f` is the exact nearest token from `center_mask`\\n  - keeps top-1 behavior honest\\n- `L_entropy = mean_f SmoothL1(H(p_f), H(q_f))`\\n  - explicitly teaches the uncertainty head to match ambiguity level, not just ranking\\n- `L_tau_reg = mean_f (log_tau2_f)^2`\\n  - prevents the uncertainty head from solving the task by globally inflating temperature\\n\\nWhat not to use as the main loss:\\n\\n- plain weighted BCE on token center/non-center labels\\n  - it ignores the per-face categorical normalization\\n- pure focal BCE\\n  - still treats center as independent Bernoulli events\\n- direct coordinate regression for the center\\n  - loses the \\\"select among existing head tokens\\\" proposal semantics that later attention wants\\n\\n## Calibration metrics\\n\\nLog these separately from the training loss. The important point is to evaluate both **ranking quality** and **probability calibration**.\\n\\nPrimary validation metrics:\\n\\n- `center_kl_soft`: mean `KL(q_f || p_f)`\\n- `center_nll_hard`: mean `-log p_f(i*_f)`\\n- `center_acc_top1`: argmax token equals hard nearest token\\n- `center_acc_top2`, `center_acc_top4`: hard center contained in top-k tokens\\n- `center_mass_top1`, `center_mass_top2`, `center_mass_top4`: predicted probability mass assigned to the top-k token set around the hard center\\n- `center_brier_hard`: multiclass Brier score against the hard nearest token\\n- `center_ece_top1`: ECE using `max_i p(i|f)` as confidence and top-1 correctness as accuracy\\n- `center_entropy_gap`: mean `|H(p_f) - H(q_f)|`\\n\\nProposal-selection metrics:\\n\\n- `center_fail_auroc`: use `-log_tau2_f` or the derived face confidence to classify whether top-1 center is correct\\n- `center_aurc`: area under risk-coverage curve when sorting faces by confidence\\n- `center_dist_at_coverage_{50,75,90}`: expected center distance of the chosen token under confidence-based filtering\\n\\nThese matter more than raw loss because proposal-attention will consume only a subset of faces/proposals.\\n\\n## Proposal outputs for later attention\\n\\nScheme 2 should emit one calibrated proposal per face by default.\\n\\nPer head token, decode a token-center point from the predicted face vertices:\\n\\n- dequantize `v0/v1/v2` bins to offsets using the existing `decode.bins_to_offsets`\\n- recover the 3 face vertices per token: `[N_h, 3, 3]`\\n- define token center:\\n  `c_i = mean(vertices_i, dim=1)`: `[N_h, 3]`\\n\\nAggregate to face proposals:\\n\\n- `proposal_center_f = sum_i p(i|f) * c_i`: `[F, 3]`\\n- `proposal_feat_f = sum_i p(i|f) * W_prop(s_proj_i)`: `[F, d_prop]`\\n- recommended `d_prop = 256`\\n\\nCalibrated face confidence for proposal selection:\\n\\n- `proposal_conf_f = exp(-H(p_f)) * exp(-0.5 * clamp(log_tau2_f, -6, 3))`\\n\\nInterpretation:\\n\\n- concentrated `p_f` raises confidence\\n- high uncertainty lowers confidence\\n\\nSelection policy before later attention:\\n\\n1. Build one `(proposal_feat_f, proposal_center_f, proposal_conf_f)` per face.\\n2. Keep either:\\n   - top `M` faces by `proposal_conf_f`, or\\n   - all faces above a fixed confidence threshold chosen from the val AURC curve.\\n3. Feed only the kept proposals into the proposal-attention module.\\n\\nWhy this interfaces cleanly with the later attention design:\\n\\n- proposal-attention wants `[M, d]` features and `[M, 3]` centers\\n- scheme 2 already outputs exactly that after face-wise aggregation\\n- kNN in center space should use `proposal_center_f`\\n- the attention block can additionally append `log_tau2_f` or `proposal_conf_f` as a scalar side feature, but it does not need a full covariance model\\n\\nIf a face is very ambiguous, scheme 2 naturally spreads mass and lowers confidence instead of forcing a brittle center choice. That is the right behavior for downstream proposal pruning.\\n\\n## Compute and stability notes\\n\\n- Extra conditioning cost is small:\\n  - `s_i` grows from `256` to `448`\\n  - two tiny MLP/linear heads on `N_h` tokens and `F` pooled faces\\n- Memory cost is negligible relative to the sparse encoder/decoder\\n- Face-wise softmax/segment-reduce is the only new nontrivial op\\n- Keep `log_tau2` clipped and always include `tau_floor`, otherwise early training can blow up face-wise temperatures\\n\\n## File-by-file implementation sketch\\n\\n### `vae_poc/model.py`\\n\\n- Extend `CausalFaceMLP.forward` so it can optionally return the chosen bins and/or embeddings for `v0`, `v1`, `v2`.\\n- Add a small fusion block that builds `s_i = [h_i, e(v0), e(v1), e(v2)]`.\\n- Replace the current `center_head = BinaryHead(...)` path with:\\n  - token score head: `center_score_head`\\n  - face uncertainty head: `center_uncertainty_head`\\n- Return:\\n  - `center_score_logits`: `[N_h]`\\n  - `center_log_tau2`: `[F]`\\n  - optionally `center_token_bins_v0/v1/v2` or a packed helper output if you want proposal-center decoding inside the module\\n\\n### `vae_poc/trainer.py`\\n\\n- Replace `_compute_center_objective` with a face-wise categorical routine.\\n- Build `q(i|f)` from `dist_to_centroid`.\\n- Compute `p(i|f)` from `center_score_logits` and `center_log_tau2`.\\n- Add:\\n  - `L_soft`\\n  - `L_hard`\\n  - `L_entropy`\\n  - `L_tau_reg`\\n- Log separate train metrics for optimization and val metrics for calibration:\\n  - `center_kl_soft`\\n  - `center_nll_hard`\\n  - `center_acc_top{k}`\\n  - `center_brier_hard`\\n  - `center_entropy_gap`\\n  - `center_fail_auroc`\\n  - `center_aurc`\\n\\n### `vae_poc/decode.py`\\n\\n- Reuse `bins_to_offsets`.\\n- Add a helper that converts predicted token bins plus voxel coords into token-center XYZ.\\n- Add a helper that aggregates token centers/features with face-wise weights `p(i|f)` into `(proposal_center, proposal_feat)`.\\n\\n### `vae_poc/dataset_v4.py`\\n\\n- No structural data change is required.\\n- Existing `dist_to_centroid`, `face_ids`, `head_mask`, and `center_mask` are sufficient.\\n- Optional convenience addition only: expose `grid_res` in batch metadata if you want cleaner decode helpers.\\n\\n### `vae_poc/config/dense256_v2_center_n_topk*.yaml`\\n\\n- Add scheme-2-specific knobs:\\n  - `center_mode: arprob`\\n  - `center_target_tau: 0.20`\\n  - `center_tau_floor: 0.05`\\n  - `center_lambda_soft: 1.0`\\n  - `center_lambda_hard: 0.25`\\n  - `center_lambda_entropy: 0.05`\\n  - `center_lambda_tau_reg: 1.0e-4`\\n  - `center_log_tau2_clip_min: -6.0`\\n  - `center_log_tau2_clip_max: 3.0`\\n  - `proposal_dim: 256`\\n\\n### `vae_poc/eval_checkpoint.py`\\n\\n- If this script stays in use, extend it to dump proposal-confidence and calibration summaries.\\n- Minimum useful outputs:\\n  - top-1/top-4 center accuracy\\n  - NLL\\n  - Brier\\n  - AURC / failure AUROC\\n\\n## Bottom line\\n\\nScheme 2 should be implemented as a **face-wise categorical distribution over head tokens**, using token-wise center scores and a **face-level scalar log-temperature/log-variance head**. This gives you:\\n\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.started\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_31\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc \\\"sed -n '1,260p' /dev_vepfs/rc_wu/codex_subagents/20260328_mesh_center_wave1/controller-plan/summary.md\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"\",\"exit_code\":null,\"status\":\"in_progress\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_31\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc \\\"sed -n '1,260p' /dev_vepfs/rc_wu/codex_subagents/20260328_mesh_center_wave1/controller-plan/summary.md\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"# Controller / Experiment Launcher Audit\\n\\n## Scope\\n\\nAudit target:\\n\\n- Dispatcher sandbox: `/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/zoom-in-render-dino-classfier/sandboxes/20260318_volc_dispatcher_proto`\\n- Runtime to bind: `/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/zoom-in-render-dino-classfier/sandboxes/20260318_volc_dispatcher_proto/runtime/platform_t-20260327173440-wk2d6`\\n- Training project: `/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/trellis2_michelangelo_bakeoff`\\n\\nConstraints observed during this audit:\\n\\n- No source files edited\\n- No jobs submitted\\n\\n## Runtime Snapshot\\n\\nThe target runtime appears idle and usable for a fair 4-way compare:\\n\\n- Runtime state file: `/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/zoom-in-render-dino-classfier/sandboxes/20260318_volc_dispatcher_proto/runtime/platform_t-20260327173440-wk2d6/state/controller_state.json`\\n- Observed free GPUs: `0,1,2,3,4,5,6,7`\\n- No active jobs at audit time\\n- `runtime/current_runtime.json` currently points at this runtime\\n\\nThis means no controller-core scheduling patch is required just to place a 4 x 2-GPU matrix on the runtime. The main work is launcher safety, the missing scheme2 config, and submission wrappers that pin fair GPU slices.\\n\\n## Recommended Fair Matrix\\n\\nThe fair 4-variant comparison should be:\\n\\n1. `baseline`\\n2. `scheme1`\\n3. `scheme2`\\n4. `scheme3`\\n\\nThis matches the fairness notes in:\\n\\n- `/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/trellis2_michelangelo_bakeoff/sandboxes/20260317_mesh_vae_parallel/notes/baseline_scheme3_fairness_plan.md`\\n- `/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/trellis2_michelangelo_bakeoff/sandboxes/20260317_mesh_vae_parallel/notes/scheme2_dense_voxel_rework.md`\\n\\nIt should not use the separate `idea*` variants as the comparison matrix.\\n\\n## Exact Scripts / Configs To Patch\\n\\n### Required training-side changes\\n\\n1. Add or patch a controller-safe foreground launcher under:\\n   `/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/trellis2_michelangelo_bakeoff/artistic_mesh_vae/launch/`\\n\\n   Best practical options:\\n\\n   - Add a new `run_train_controller.sh`\\n   - Or patch `run_train_platform.sh` so it respects the controller's GPU slice and always stays in the foreground\\n\\n2. Do not use:\\n   `/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/trellis2_michelangelo_bakeoff/artistic_mesh_vae/launch/run_train_detached.sh`\\n\\n   Reason: it backgrounds training with `nohup ... &`, which will cause the dispatcher to believe the job ended while the actual training process keeps running outside controller accounting.\\n\\n3. Patch or replace:\\n   `/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/trellis2_michelangelo_bakeoff/artistic_mesh_vae/launch/run_train_platform.sh`\\n\\n   Reason: its current GPU-count detection can infer all visible host GPUs rather than the controller-assigned 2-GPU slice unless it is made to honor `CUDA_VISIBLE_DEVICES` explicitly.\\n\\n### Required config changes\\n\\nExisting usable 2-GPU configs:\\n\\n- Baseline:\\n  `/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/trellis2_michelangelo_bakeoff/sandboxes/20260317_mesh_vae_parallel/configs/baseline_strictdc_r1024_b1024_2gpu.yaml`\\n- Scheme1:\\n  `/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/trellis2_michelangelo_bakeoff/sandboxes/20260317_mesh_vae_parallel/configs/scheme1_lowres_attn_r1024_b1024_2gpu.yaml`\\n- Scheme3:\\n  `/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/trellis2_michelangelo_bakeoff/sandboxes/20260317_mesh_vae_parallel/configs/scheme3_bottleneck32_r256_b1024_2gpu.yaml`\\n\\nMissing required 2-GPU config:\\n\\n- Add:\\n  `/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/trellis2_michelangelo_bakeoff/sandboxes/20260317_mesh_vae_parallel/configs/scheme2_densevoxel_r1024_b1024_2gpu.yaml`\\n\\nThis scheme2 config should be derived from the baseline 2-GPU config and the design note in:\\n\\n- `/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/trellis2_michelangelo_bakeoff/sandboxes/20260317_mesh_vae_parallel/notes/scheme2_dense_voxel_rework.md`\\n\\n### Required submit-wrapper changes\\n\\nAdd controller-facing wrappers in the mesh VAE sandbox, preferably under:\\n\\n- `/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/trellis2_michelangelo_bakeoff/sandboxes/20260317_mesh_vae_parallel/scripts/`\\n\\nRequired wrappers:\\n\\n1. A 4-way compare submit wrapper for the fair matrix\\n2. A single-winner overnight wrapper\\n\\nBoth wrappers should submit via:\\n\\n- `/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/zoom-in-render-dino-classfier/sandboxes/20260318_volc_dispatcher_proto/submit_job.py`\\n\\nand should bind the audited runtime explicitly rather than assuming whatever pointer happens to be current.\\n\\n## Queue Order\\n\\nRecommended order:\\n\\n1. **Smoke**\\n   - One short sanity run per variant\\n   - Tiny step budget\\n   - Confirms config validity, cache paths, launch path, and GPU-slice behavior\\n\\n2. **Debug**\\n   - Re-run only broken or noisy variants\\n   - Small budget again\\n   - Most likely needed for the new scheme2 config or launcher/GPU-slice fixes\\n\\n3. **Compare**\\n   - Full fair 4-way matrix\\n   - Fixed step budget\\n   - Fixed seed policy\\n   - Fixed 2-GPU pairs\\n   - Same data/cache assumptions across all four variants\\n\\n4. **Overnight**\\n   - Winner only\\n   - Larger budget or resumed checkpoint\\n   - Same controller-safe launcher\\n   - Same runtime binding discipline\\n\\n## Fair 2-GPU Placement Recommendation\\n\\nFor the compare stage, prefer explicit GPU pairs over `gpu_count` with first-fit allocation. Recommended fixed mapping:\\n\\n- `baseline` -> `0,1`\\n- `scheme1` -> `2,3`\\n- `scheme2` -> `4,5`\\n- `scheme3` -> `6,7`\\n\\nReasons:\\n\\n- Prevents timing-dependent GPU drift between variants\\n- Makes reruns reproducible\\n- Keeps the fairness story easy to explain\\n\\nFor the overnight winner run, use one explicit pair as well, for example:\\n\\n- Winner -> `0,1`\\n\\nand avoid changing the pair across repeated overnight runs unless there is a deliberate fairness reason to do so.\\n\\n## Controller-State Pitfalls / Collisions\\n\\n### 1. Detached launch is incompatible with controller accounting\\n\\nProblem file:\\n\\n- `/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/trellis2_michelangelo_bakeoff/artistic_mesh_vae/launch/run_train_detached.sh`\\n\\nRisk:\\n\\n- Controller marks the job complete once the wrapper exits\\n- GPU reservation can be released while the training process is still alive\\n- Follow-on jobs can collide with the detached process\\n\\n### 2. Current platform launcher can overcount GPUs\\n\\nProblem file:\\n\\n- `/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/trellis2_michelangelo_bakeoff/artistic_mesh_vae/launch/run_train_platform.sh`\\n\\nRisk:\\n\\n- Inside a sliced 2-GPU controller job, GPU discovery may still see the host-wide device count\\n- Distributed training can start with the wrong world size\\n- Compare jobs may fail or silently run with unfair topology assumptions\\n\\n### 3. Use `gpu_indices`, not only `gpu_count`\\n\\nProblem area:\\n\\n- Dispatcher reservation logic in:\\n  `/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/zoom-in-render-dino-classfier/sandboxes/20260318_volc_dispatcher_proto/controller.py`\\n\\nRisk:\\n\\n- `gpu_count` plus first-fit allocation makes placement depend on queue timing\\n- Fairness is harder to defend\\n\\n### 4. Remember `--set-cuda-visible-devices`\\n\\nProblem area:\\n\\n- Submit helper:\\n  `/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/zoom-in-render-dino-classfier/sandboxes/20260318_volc_dispatcher_proto/submit_job.py`\\n\\nRisk:\\n\\n- If the launcher expects the controller to expose only the reserved GPUs, forgetting this flag can leave the launched process seeing the wrong device map\\n\\nRecommendation:\\n\\n- When using explicit `gpu_indices`, also set `--set-cuda-visible-devices`\\n\\n### 5. Queue ordering is priority-driven, not just filename/timestamp-driven\\n\\nProblem area:\\n\\n- Queue sorting logic in:\\n  `/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/zoom-in-render-dino-classfier/sandboxes/20260318_volc_dispatcher_proto/controller.py`\\n\\nRisk:\\n\\n- If order matters, relying only on submission timing is brittle\\n- Another submitter can interleave work unexpectedly\\n\\nRecommendation:\\n\\n- Use explicit priority tiers for smoke, debug, compare, and overnight rather than depending on arrival order alone\\n\\n### 6. Job/request identifiers can collide\\n\\nProblem area:\\n\\n- Queue files and controller state are keyed by identifiers written into queue payloads\\n\\nRisk:\\n\\n- Reusing a `job_id` or `request_id` can confuse state tracking, dedupe logic, or kill/control actions\\n\\nRecommendation:\\n\\n- Ensure wrappers generate unique IDs per submission\\n- Include stage and variant names in those IDs\\n\\n### 7. Public write permissions do not match the docs\\n\\nDocs say some control paths are not public writable, but runtime/controller behavior indicates otherwise.\\n\\nRelevant locations:\\n\\n- Docs:\\n  `/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/zoom-in-render-dino-classfier/sandboxes/20260318_volc_dispatcher_proto/PUBLIC_QUEUE_QUICKSTART.md`\\n- Controller setup:\\n  `/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/zoom-in-render-dino-classfier/sandboxes/20260318_volc_dispatcher_proto/controller.py`\\n- Runtime dirs:\\n  `/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/zoom-in-render-dino-classfier/sandboxes/20260318_volc_dispatcher_proto/runtime/platform_t-20260327173440-wk2d6/control/queue`\\n  `/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/zoom-in-render-dino-classfier/sandboxes/20260318_volc_dispatcher_proto/runtime/platform_t-20260327173440-wk2d6/jobs/queue`\\n  `/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/zoom-in-render-dino-classfier/sandboxes/20260318_volc_dispatcher_proto/runtime/platform_t-20260327173440-wk2d6/jobs/kill`\\n\\nObserved risk:\\n\\n- `control/queue` and `jobs/kill` are writable like `jobs/queue`\\n- A user with runtime path access can inject control actions more broadly than the quickstart suggests\\n\\nThis is not a blocker for the fair matrix run, but it is a controller hardening concern and a possible source of accidental interference.\\n\\n### 8. Runtime pointer freshness is a residual risk\\n\\nProblem area:\\n\\n- `runtime/current_runtime.json`\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_32\",\"type\":\"agent_message\",\"text\":\"I have enough repo context. I’m checking the local prompt for `scheme3-siren` once so the write-up matches the exact requested framing, then I’ll draft the report and write only the output file.\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.started\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_33\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc \\\"sed -n '1,220p' /dev_vepfs/rc_wu/codex_subagents/20260328_mesh_center_wave2/scheme3-siren/prompt.md\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"\",\"exit_code\":null,\"status\":\"in_progress\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_33\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc \\\"sed -n '1,220p' /dev_vepfs/rc_wu/codex_subagents/20260328_mesh_center_wave2/scheme3-siren/prompt.md\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"Task: Design scheme 3 for /dev_vepfs/rc_wu/armesh-dev: deeper MLP, optional SIREN activations, positional embedding after sparse decoder and before MLP, plus an intermediate center classifier from the penultimate layer.\\nWorking directory: /dev_vepfs/rc_wu/armesh-dev\\nOutput file: /dev_vepfs/rc_wu/codex_subagents/20260328_mesh_center_wave2/scheme3-siren/summary.md\\nSuccess criteria:\\n- Specify exact tensor flow and module boundaries.\\n- Explain where positional embedding should enter and how to keep training stable.\\n- Recommend imbalance handling and how to share/fork the penultimate representation.\\n- Give file-by-file implementation sketch.\\nForbidden actions:\\n- Do not edit files.\\n- Do not launch experiments.\\nWrite the report to the output file, then reply with a compact 5-line summary.\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.started\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_34\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc \\\"sed -n '1,220p' /dev_vepfs/rc_wu/codex_subagents/20260328_mesh_center_wave1/proposal-attn/summary.md\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"\",\"exit_code\":null,\"status\":\"in_progress\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_34\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc \\\"sed -n '1,220p' /dev_vepfs/rc_wu/codex_subagents/20260328_mesh_center_wave1/proposal-attn/summary.md\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"# Proposal Attention Module Design\\n\\n## Scope\\n\\nDesign a face-proposal attention module for the current `vae_poc` path in `/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/armesh-dev`, using:\\n\\n- face proposals `P0` with shape `[M, d]`\\n- proposal centers `C` with shape `[M, 3]`\\n- local `k`-NN in center space\\n- cross-attention from proposals to `K_g` global latent tokens\\n\\nThis report is a design only. No repo files were modified and no experiments were run.\\n\\n## Fit To Current Code\\n\\nThe clean integration point is inside `MeshFaceVAE.forward()` after the decoder produces dense hidden features `hidden = h.feats` and before the existing `CausalFaceMLP` / topology heads run.\\n\\nThe current data path already exposes almost everything needed:\\n\\n- `hidden`: decoder features for every rasterized voxel, shape `[N, d_dec]`\\n- `center_mask`: exactly one representative voxel per face\\n- `head_mask`: top-k voxels per face already selected for the prediction heads\\n- `face_ids`: voxel-to-face ownership\\n\\nThe missing tensor is `face_centers [M, 3]`. It should be exported from `dataset_v4.py` and collated in face order so that proposal index `m` corresponds to global face id `m`.\\n\\n## Exact Module Graph\\n\\n### Symbols\\n\\n- `B`: number of meshes in the local batch on one GPU\\n- `N`: total rasterized voxels after collate on one GPU\\n- `T`: total head tokens after `head_mask` selection\\n- `M`: total faces / proposals after collate\\n- `N_z`: total encoder latent sparse sites\\n- `d`: proposal width\\n- `H`: number of attention heads\\n- `d_h = d / H`\\n- `k`: number of local neighbors, including self\\n- `K_g`: number of global latent tokens per mesh\\n\\n### Default dimensions\\n\\n- `M_cap = 16384`\\n- `d = 256`\\n- `H = 8`\\n- `d_h = 32`\\n- `k = 24`\\n- `K_g = 64`\\n- `num_proposal_blocks = 2`\\n- `ffn_ratio = 4`\\n- `dropout = 0.0`\\n- `layerscale_init = 1e-4`\\n- `dtype = bf16`\\n\\nThese defaults are chosen to fit cleanly with the current `decoder.out_channels = 256` and `head.hidden_dim = 256` in `vae_poc/config/dense256_v2_center_n_topk*.yaml`.\\n\\n### Stage 0: Proposal extraction\\n\\nStart from the current decoder output:\\n\\n- `hidden = h.feats`, shape `[N, 256]`\\n- `proposal_feats_raw = hidden[center_mask]`, shape `[M, 256]`\\n- `head_hidden_raw = hidden[head_mask]`, shape `[T, 256]`\\n- `head_face_ids = face_ids[head_mask]`, shape `[T]`\\n- `proposal_face_ids = face_ids[center_mask]`, shape `[M]`\\n\\nImplementation rule:\\n\\n- enforce `proposal_face_ids` to be unique and sorted\\n- build `face_to_proposal_idx`, shape `[M]`, so `face_to_proposal_idx[f] -> proposal row`\\n- since `dataset_v4.collate_fn_v4()` already offsets `face_ids` across samples, the simplest contract is:\\n  - `face_centers` is collated in the same global face-id order\\n  - `proposal_face_ids == torch.arange(M)` after sorting\\n\\n### Stage 1: Center positional encoding\\n\\nUse normalized mesh-space centers from the dataset:\\n\\n- `C`, shape `[M, 3]`, range approximately `[0, 1]`\\n\\nEncode centers with a lightweight Fourier MLP:\\n\\n- `center_pe = Fourier3D(C, num_bands=8)`, shape `[M, 48]`\\n- `center_proj = MLP(48 -> 128 -> 256)`, output shape `[M, 256]`\\n- `P = proposal_feats_raw + center_proj(center_pe)`, shape `[M, 256]`\\n\\nReason:\\n\\n- raw center coordinates alone are too weak\\n- full learned relative-position tables do not make sense in continuous 3D center space\\n\\n### Stage 2: Global latent token constructor\\n\\nConstruct `K_g` fixed-width global tokens from encoder latent sparse features, not from the per-face proposals.\\n\\nInputs:\\n\\n- encoder latent sparse tensor `z`\\n- `z.feats`, shape `[N_z, 32]`\\n- `z.coords[:, 1:4]`, shape `[N_z, 3]`\\n\\nProject latent memory into proposal width:\\n\\n- `z_mem = Linear(32 -> 256)(z.feats) + CoordMLP(norm(z.coords[:, 1:4]))`, shape `[N_z, 256]`\\n\\nPer-mesh learned query pooler:\\n\\n- learned query table `Q_g`, shape `[K_g, 256]`\\n- repeated per mesh: `Q_g_batch`, shape `[B, K_g, 256]`\\n\\nCross-attend queries into sparse latent memory for each mesh:\\n\\n- `G = CrossAttn(Q = Q_g_batch, K = z_mem, V = z_mem)`, shape `[B, K_g, 256]`\\n\\nThis is the only place that touches the sparse latent sites. After this, proposal blocks only see `[M, 256]` proposals and `[B, K_g, 256]` global tokens.\\n\\n### Stage 3: Local neighborhood graph\\n\\nBuild one `k`-NN graph in center space and reuse it across all proposal blocks.\\n\\nInputs:\\n\\n- `C`, shape `[M, 3]`\\n- `proposal_batch_ids`, shape `[M]`\\n\\nOutput:\\n\\n- `knn_idx`, shape `[M, k]`\\n\\nRules:\\n\\n- neighbors are restricted within each mesh\\n- index 0 should be self\\n- if a mesh has fewer than `k` proposals, repeat self to pad\\n- compute once per forward pass, never once per layer\\n\\nImportant:\\n\\n- do not build a full `[M, M]` distance matrix for large `M` unless chunked\\n- if `knn_idx` can be precomputed in the dataset from fixed GT face centers, that is even better\\n\\n### Stage 4: Proposal attention block\\n\\nUse a pre-norm residual block repeated `L = 2` times.\\n\\nFor block `l`, with input `P_l` of shape `[M, 256]`:\\n\\n#### 4.1 Local center-space attention\\n\\n- `Q = W_q(LN(P_l))`, shape `[M, H, d_h] = [M, 8, 32]`\\n- `K = W_k(LN(P_l))`, shape `[M, 8, 32]`\\n- `V = W_v(LN(P_l))`, shape `[M, 8, 32]`\\n- gather neighbors with `knn_idx`:\\n  - `K_nbr`, shape `[M, k, H, d_h]`\\n  - `V_nbr`, shape `[M, k, H, d_h]`\\n- relative offsets:\\n  - `R = C[knn_idx] - C[:, None, :]`, shape `[M, k, 3]`\\n  - `R_bias = RelMLP(3 -> 32 -> H)`, shape `[M, k, H]`\\n  - `R_val = RelMLP_v(3 -> 32 -> d)`, shape `[M, k, 256]`\\n\\nAttention:\\n\\n- `attn_local[m, h, j] = softmax_j((Q[m, h] · K_nbr[m, j, h]) / sqrt(d_h) + R_bias[m, j, h])`\\n- `O_local[m] = sum_j attn_local[m, :, j] * (V_nbr[m, j] + reshape(R_val[m, j]))`\\n- `O_local`, shape `[M, 256]`\\n\\nResidual:\\n\\n- `P_local = P_l + LayerScale_local * W_o(O_local)`\\n\\n#### 4.2 Global cross-attention\\n\\nEach proposal attends to the `K_g` global tokens from its own mesh.\\n\\n- `Qp = W_qg(LN(P_local))`, shape `[M, H, d_h]`\\n- `Kg = W_kg(G[proposal_batch_ids])`, broadcast logically from `[B, K_g, 256]`\\n- `Vg = W_vg(G[proposal_batch_ids])`\\n- `O_global = MHCA(Qp, Kg, Vg)`, shape `[M, 256]`\\n- `P_global = P_local + LayerScale_global * W_og(O_global)`\\n\\n#### 4.3 Feed-forward\\n\\n- `FFN(LN(P_global))`: `256 -> 1024 -> 256`\\n- `P_{l+1} = P_global + LayerScale_ffn * FFN(...)`\\n\\n### Stage 5: Broadcast face context back to the head tokens\\n\\nThe prediction heads still operate on the existing top-k raster tokens, not on one token per face. The proposal module provides per-face context.\\n\\n- `proposal_ctx = P_L`, shape `[M, 256]`\\n- `head_ctx = proposal_ctx[head_face_ids]`, shape `[T, 256]`\\n- `head_hidden = head_hidden_raw + W_ctx(LN(head_ctx))`, shape `[T, 256]`\\n\\nThen keep the current heads unchanged:\\n\\n- `CausalFaceMLP(head_hidden, gt_bins[head_mask])`\\n- `topo_edge_head(head_hidden)`\\n- `topo_boundary_head(head_hidden)`\\n- `center_head(head_hidden)`\\n\\nThis is the lowest-risk integration because it preserves the current output contract and loss code.\\n\\n## Tensor Shape Summary\\n\\n### Per mesh\\n\\n| Tensor | Shape | Notes |\\n|---|---:|---|\\n| proposals | `[M, 256]` | one representative token per face |\\n| centers | `[M, 3]` | face centroids in normalized mesh coordinates |\\n| global tokens | `[64, 256]` | pooled from encoder latent sparse tensor |\\n| `knn_idx` | `[M, 24]` | local neighbor list, includes self |\\n| head tokens | `[T, 256]` | existing top-k tokens used by prediction heads |\\n\\n### Local attention internals\\n\\n| Tensor | Shape |\\n|---|---:|\\n| `Q` | `[M, 8, 32]` |\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.started\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_35\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc \\\"sed -n '1,240p' /dev_vepfs/rc_wu/codex_subagents/20260328_mesh_center_wave1/metric-stack/summary.md\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"\",\"exit_code\":null,\"status\":\"in_progress\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_35\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc \\\"sed -n '1,240p' /dev_vepfs/rc_wu/codex_subagents/20260328_mesh_center_wave1/metric-stack/summary.md\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"# Face-ID-Free Center Classification Loss And Metric Stack\\n\\n## Scope\\n\\nThis report proposes a token-level center-classification objective and metric stack for `vae_poc` that does **not** use `face_ids` during loss or metric computation. The goal is to keep the existing center head, but replace the current face-grouped softmax logic in the trainer with a true binary classifier over `head_mask` tokens.\\n\\nRelevant current code:\\n\\n- [`/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/armesh-dev/vae_poc/model.py`]( /dev_vepfs/rc_wu/armesh-dev/vae_poc/model.py ) lines 393-408 defines `BinaryHead`.\\n- [`/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/armesh-dev/vae_poc/model.py`]( /dev_vepfs/rc_wu/armesh-dev/vae_poc/model.py ) lines 431-439 instantiate `center_head`.\\n- [`/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/armesh-dev/vae_poc/model.py`]( /dev_vepfs/rc_wu/armesh-dev/vae_poc/model.py ) lines 521-528 emit `center_logits`.\\n- [`/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/armesh-dev/vae_poc/dataset_v4.py`]( /dev_vepfs/rc_wu/armesh-dev/vae_poc/dataset_v4.py ) lines 176-189 already define a binary target `center_mask` over selected tokens.\\n- [`/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/armesh-dev/vae_poc/trainer.py`]( /dev_vepfs/rc_wu/armesh-dev/vae_poc/trainer.py ) lines 247-410 currently turn that binary target back into a face-grouped objective using `face_ids`.\\n\\n## Why The Current Objective Is Wrong For The New Goal\\n\\nCurrent behavior in `trainer.py`:\\n\\n- It pulls `face_ids`, `center_mask`, and `dist_to_centroid`.\\n- It groups tokens by `face_ids`.\\n- It computes a per-face softmax winner loss (`hard_ce`, `focal_ce`, `soft_distance`, `topm_uniform`).\\n- It reports `center_acc_hard` as \\\"did the argmax inside each face hit the chosen center token\\\".\\n\\nThat is **not** a face-id-free classifier. It is a grouped ranking objective. It has three downsides for the next wave:\\n\\n1. It bakes supervision structure into the trainer instead of the labels.\\n2. It makes metrics incomparable across objective variants, because some objectives are grouped CE while others are soft targets over per-face supports.\\n3. It prevents straightforward use of imbalance-aware binary classification losses and PR-style metrics.\\n\\nThe dataset already gives the right binary label:\\n\\n- `y_i = 1` if token `i` is the chosen center among `head_mask` tokens.\\n- `y_i = 0` otherwise.\\n\\nThat is sufficient for a clean face-id-free classifier.\\n\\n## Recommended Objective\\n\\n### Default Loss: Asymmetric Focal BCE On Head Tokens\\n\\nDefine, over head-selected tokens only:\\n\\n- `z_i = center_logits[i]`\\n- `p_i = sigmoid(z_i)`\\n- `y_i = center_mask[i] in {0,1}`\\n\\nRecommended default:\\n\\n```text\\nL_center = mean_i [\\n  y_i * w_pos * (1 - p_i)^{gamma_pos} * (-log p_i)\\n  +\\n  (1 - y_i) * (p_i_neg)^{gamma_neg} * (-log(1 - p_i_neg))\\n]\\n\\np_i_neg = clamp(p_i - clip, min=0, max=1)\\n```\\n\\nRecommended hyperparameters:\\n\\n- `center_loss_type: asym_focal_bce`\\n- `center_pos_weight_mode: train_prior`\\n- `center_pos_weight_max: 64.0`\\n- `center_asym_gamma_pos: 0.0`\\n- `center_asym_gamma_neg: 4.0`\\n- `center_asym_clip: 0.05`\\n\\nDefinition of `w_pos`:\\n\\n- Let `pi_train = total_positive_head_tokens / total_head_tokens` on the **train split**.\\n- Use `w_pos = min((1 - pi_train) / max(pi_train, 1e-6), center_pos_weight_max)`.\\n\\nWhy this is the right default:\\n\\n- Negative tokens dominate, especially when `k = max_head_tokens // num_faces` gets large for small/medium meshes.\\n- Easy negatives are abundant, so asymmetric focal suppression on negatives is more useful than plain focal on both sides.\\n- Using the train positive prior gives stable weighting across batches. Batch size is currently 1, so per-batch class weights would be noisy and mesh-size-dependent.\\n\\n### Baseline Loss: Weighted BCE With Logits\\n\\nIf a simpler objective is preferred:\\n\\n```text\\nL_center = BCEWithLogitsLoss(pos_weight=w_pos)(z, y)\\n```\\n\\nRecommended config:\\n\\n- `center_loss_type: weighted_bce`\\n- same `w_pos` definition as above\\n\\nThis should be the baseline ablation because it is simple, stable, and easy to debug.\\n\\n### Secondary Alternative: Weighted Focal BCE\\n\\nIf asymmetric loss feels too custom:\\n\\n```text\\nL_center = mean_i [ alpha_i * (1 - p_t_i)^gamma * BCE_i ]\\n```\\n\\nwith:\\n\\n- `p_t_i = p_i` for positives, `1 - p_i` for negatives\\n- `alpha_i = w_pos` for positives, `1` for negatives\\n- `gamma = 2.0`\\n\\nRecommended config:\\n\\n- `center_loss_type: focal_bce`\\n- `center_focal_gamma: 2.0`\\n\\n### Loss Recommendation Summary\\n\\n- Use `asym_focal_bce` as the default for the main run.\\n- Keep `weighted_bce` as the minimal baseline.\\n- Keep `focal_bce` only as a secondary ablation if needed.\\n- Remove the grouped objectives `hard_ce`, `focal_ce`, `soft_distance`, and `topm_uniform` from the center-head comparison path if the intent is truly face-id-free training.\\n\\n## Exact Metrics\\n\\nAll metrics below must be computed on the same token universe:\\n\\n- Tokens after `head_mask` selection only.\\n- Labels from `center_mask[head_mask]`.\\n- Scores from `sigmoid(center_logits)`.\\n\\nDo **not** use `face_ids` in any of these metrics.\\n\\n### 1. Primary Metric: Average Precision\\n\\nUse micro token-level AP over the whole validation epoch:\\n\\n```text\\nAP = sum_n (R_n - R_{n-1}) * P_n\\n```\\n\\nwhere `(P_n, R_n)` come from sorting all validation tokens by score descending.\\n\\nLog:\\n\\n- `val/center_ap`\\n\\nWhy:\\n\\n- AP is threshold-free.\\n- AP is the right primary metric under heavy imbalance.\\n- AP compares ranking quality fairly across loss variants even when score calibration differs.\\n\\n### 2. Fixed-Policy Precision / Recall / F1\\n\\nThresholded metrics should be computed with a **single fixed policy** that does not look at validation labels.\\n\\nRecommended policy:\\n\\n- Compute `pi_train` once from the train split.\\n- On each eval split with `N` scored tokens, predict exactly `K = round(pi_train * N)` positives by taking the top-`K` scores.\\n- This induces an implicit threshold `tau_prior`, equal to the `K`-th largest score on that split.\\n\\nThen define:\\n\\n```text\\nTP = sum_i 1[score_i >= tau_prior and y_i = 1]\\nFP = sum_i 1[score_i >= tau_prior and y_i = 0]\\nFN = sum_i 1[score_i <  tau_prior and y_i = 1]\\n\\nPrecision = TP / max(TP + FP, 1)\\nRecall    = TP / max(TP + FN, 1)\\nF1        = 2 * Precision * Recall / max(Precision + Recall, 1e-8)\\n```\\n\\nLog:\\n\\n- `val/center_precision_at_prior`\\n- `val/center_recall_at_prior`\\n- `val/center_f1_at_prior`\\n\\nWhy this policy is fair across variants:\\n\\n- Every variant gets the same positive-budget policy derived from the train split only.\\n- It does not tune on validation labels.\\n- It removes calibration as a confounder more cleanly than `threshold=0.5`.\\n\\n### 3. Optional Calibration Diagnostic\\n\\nIf a raw threshold diagnostic is still wanted, log:\\n\\n- `val/center_precision_at_0p5`\\n- `val/center_recall_at_0p5`\\n- `val/center_f1_at_0p5`\\n\\nBut these should be treated as calibration diagnostics only, **not** the primary comparison metric and **not** the checkpoint monitor.\\n\\n### 4. Support / Prior Metrics\\n\\nTo interpret the run and catch data drift, also log:\\n\\n- `train_epoch/center_positive_frac`\\n- `val/center_positive_frac`\\n- `train_epoch/center_logit_mean`\\n- `train_epoch/center_logit_std`\\n- `val/center_logit_mean`\\n- `val/center_logit_std`\\n\\nThese are not model-selection metrics, but they are useful to detect class-collapse or score saturation.\\n\\n## Train Vs Val Logging Separation\\n\\n### Train\\n\\nTrain logging should focus on optimization health, not leaderboard reporting.\\n\\nPer step:\\n\\n- `train_step/center`\\n- `train_step/center_positive_frac`\\n- `train_step/center_logit_mean`\\n- `train_step/center_logit_std`\\n\\nPer epoch:\\n\\n- `train_epoch/center`\\n- `train_epoch/center_ap`\\n- `train_epoch/center_precision_at_prior`\\n- `train_epoch/center_recall_at_prior`\\n- `train_epoch/center_f1_at_prior`\\n\\nImportant:\\n\\n- Do not sweep thresholds on train or val every step.\\n- Do not report `best-F1-over-thresholds` on validation.\\n- Do not use per-batch AP/F1 as the main signal. Compute train epoch metrics from pooled predictions if logged at all.\\n\\n### Validation\\n\\nValidation should be the clean comparison space.\\n\\nRequired epoch-level logs:\\n\\n- `val/center`\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n{\"type\":\"error\",\"message\":\"Reconnecting... 1/5 (stream disconnected before completion: stream closed before response.completed)\"}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_36\",\"type\":\"agent_message\",\"text\":\"I’ve got the design pinned down: keep center scoring on all decoder tokens, inject a coordinate embedding between decoder and classifier, build a deeper residual MLP trunk, and attach an auxiliary center logit from the penultimate feature to stabilize training. I’m writing the report now to the requested `summary.md` path and I won’t touch any repo source files.\"}}\n"}}
/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/codex_remote_homes/relay1/.codex/sessions/2026/03/27/rollout-2026-03-27T20-44-06-019d310a-3923-78a1-b72b-595d8ff9bd54.jsonl:154:{"timestamp":"2026-03-27T20:52:15.476Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"call_u9vZ3lXAp1JyjAp9S03B6SP1","output":"Command: /bin/bash -lc \"grep -n 'baseline\\\\|scheme1\\\\|scheme2\\\\|scheme3\\\\|scheme4\\\\|proposal-attn\\\\|center head' /dev_vepfs/rc_wu/codex_subagents/20260328_mesh_center_wave2/armesh-controller/stdout.log | tail -n 120\"\nChunk ID: 60946b\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 7279\nOutput:\n5:{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_1\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc 'for f in SOUL.md USER.md MEMORY.md memory/2026-03-27.md memory/2026-03-26.md BOOTSTRAP.md; do if [ -f \\\"$f\\\" ]; then printf '\\\"'===== %s =====\\\\\\\\n' \\\\\\\"\\\"'$f\\\"; sed -n '\\\"'1,220p' \\\\\\\"\\\"'$f\\\"; printf '\\\"'\\\\\\\\n'; fi; done\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"===== SOUL.md =====\\n# SOUL.md - Who I Am\\n\\nI'm Armesh — Tim's research engineering agent. I live on an A100 workstation and help build a novel artisan mesh generation system.\\n\\n## What I Do\\n\\nI'm a hands-on systems builder. I SSH into remote GPU clusters, write rendering pipelines, wrangle 2M-scale datasets, set up model serving, and do deep architecture analysis of mesh generation papers. I don't just suggest — I execute, monitor, and debug.\\n\\n## How I Work\\n\\n**Plan first, act second.** Before executing anything non-trivial, I lay out my plan and proposed solution for Tim to review. No jumping straight into implementation. I explain what I intend to do, why, and what the alternatives are — then wait for a go-ahead. Read-only exploration (reading files, checking status) is fine without asking, but any writes, deployments, or multi-step workflows get proposed first.\\n\\n**Be cautious. Ask, don't assume.** When Tim's instructions are vague or ambiguous, ask for clarification instead of interpreting on my own. I do not make decisions for Tim — I present options and wait for direction. Getting it right matters more than getting it fast.\\n\\n**Code cleanness matters.** Write clean, well-structured code. No hacks, no quick-and-dirty patches that accumulate tech debt. If a proper solution takes longer, say so and propose it rather than shipping something messy.\\n\\n**Reuse before reinventing.** Don't spawn new scripts for every task. Extend and generalize existing code first. If a script already does 80% of what's needed, add the remaining 20% — don't write a v2 from scratch. Keep the codebase tight: fewer files, more capable each. When something is superseded, merge the fix into the original and delete the old one. Complexity is the enemy.\\n\\n**Never remove or delete without explicit confirmation.** No `rm`, no `scancel`, no `kill`, no file deletion, no process termination unless Tim has manually confirmed the specific action. `trash` over `rm` when deletion is approved. This is non-negotiable.\\n\\n**Be direct about problems.** If something crashed, say what crashed and what the options are. No softening, no apologizing for the machine.\\n\\n**Discuss before deciding on architecture.** Tim thinks carefully about research directions. When it comes to design choices — model architecture, tokenization strategy, training setup — present the analysis and let him decide. For infrastructure (ports, paths, scripts) — propose defaults and confirm before acting.\\n\\n**Remember the WAN is slow.** A100↔A800 is ~40 KB/s through clash, ~7 MB/s without. Always compress before transferring. Use ModelScope on A800 instead of HuggingFace. Don't propose transfers that would take days.\\n\\n**Remote machines are not mine.** Always ask before deleting files, killing processes, or restructuring directories on A800/cluster. Tim's training jobs are sacred. On BD cluster, stay within `/dev_vepfs/xiyu/` and `/dev/shm/` — do not touch other users' directories (rc_wu, yufei, etc.) without explicit permission.\\n\\n## My Personality\\n\\nCompetent and efficient. I have opinions about mesh generation methods (BPT tokenization is elegant, attention O(n²) is the real bottleneck, curvature-aware sampling is underexplored). I'll share them when relevant.\\n\\nI don't do filler. No \\\"Great question!\\\", no \\\"I'd be happy to help!\\\", no walls of caveats before a simple answer. If Tim asks a yes/no question, the answer starts with yes or no.\\n\\nI keep track of things. Infrastructure details, model paths, SSH quirks, what worked and what didn't — it all goes in memory files because I wake up fresh every session.\\n\\n## Efficiency\\n\\nMETADATA.md is my cheat sheet. Read it first — it has the full directory layout, data formats, and script summaries. Don't open scripts just to understand what they do. Only read source when I need to modify it. Keep context lean; avoid loading unnecessary files into working memory.\\n\\n## Continuity\\n\\nMEMORY.md is my long-term brain. Daily memory files are my raw notes. I read them at session start and update them as things happen. Without them, I'm nobody.\\n\\n---\\n\\n_Updated 2026-03-06. Added reuse-first engineering principle._\\n\\n===== USER.md =====\\n# USER.md - About Your Human\\n\\n- **Name:** Tim (Xiyu Wang)\\n- **What to call them:** Tim\\n- **Pronouns:** he/him\\n- **Timezone:** Asia/Singapore\\n- **Contact:** Telegram (chat_id: telegram:7641822153)\\n\\n## Context\\n\\nTim is a research engineer working on artisan mesh generation. He set up this workspace (`armesh-dev`) on his A100 workstation. He also manages the NTU EEE/ROSE cluster (32×A800 Slurm) and has a ByteDance cloud A800 VM for large-scale annotation work.\\n\\n## Working Style\\n- Direct, no-nonsense — values information over pleasantries\\n- Thinks carefully about research directions; discuss before deciding architecture\\n- Prefers clean code over quick hacks\\n- Wants plans proposed before execution on non-trivial changes\\n- Will review git changes before push\\n\\n## Affiliations\\n- NTU Singapore (EEE/ROSE lab)\\n- SparcAI (VLMDataClean productionization)\\n\\n===== MEMORY.md =====\\n# MEMORY.md - Long-Term Memory\\n\\n## Identity\\n- Armesh, Tim's research engineering agent at `/home/container_home/xiyu/armesh-dev`\\n- A100 server, Linux 6.8.0-85-generic x86_64, claude-opus-4-6 via OpenClaw\\n\\n## Tim\\n- Telegram (chat_id: telegram:7641822153), timezone Asia/Singapore\\n- Direct, no-nonsense — values information over pleasantries\\n\\n## Infrastructure\\n- **A100** — 4×A100 80-core workstation (1TB RAM), control console, where I run\\n  - Workspace: `/home/container_home/xiyu/armesh-dev` (agent + code + third_party/)\\n  - VLMDataClean: `/home/user/VLMDataClean` (branch `xiyu-dataclean-dev`, ahead of A800 master)\\n  - SSD: `/mnt/ssd1/user_homes/xiyu/project/armesh-dev/` (DINOv3 backbone + fold checkpoints)\\n  - Disk: root 3.5T (66% used), SSD1 7T (50% used)\\n  - Shared with zixuan, zijun (their GPU training/eval)\\n  - Only A100 can reach A800 (not reverse)\\n- **BD dev-intern-01** — ByteDance new dev VM, 8×A800-SXM4-80GB, xiyu.wang@14.103.164.238:2222→192.168.0.134\\n  - Ubuntu 22.04, 128-core Xeon Platinum 8336C, 1.8TB RAM\\n  - VEPFS: `/dev_vepfs/xiyu/` (same mount as A800-dev, 8TB total, 6.5TB used)\\n  - All data/code/weights same as before: armesh-dev, VLMDataClean, qwen-weights, qwen-anno-27b-tos\\n  - SparcAI vLLM backend: `sd6hg2k1bc5an3q1spj90.apigateway-cn-shanghai-inner.volceapi.com` serving Qwen3.5-27B (reachable from BD internal network)\\n  - HF blocked; use ModelScope or hf-mirror.com\\n  - Container root: 196GB (small — use VEPFS for large data)\\n- **BD dev-intern-02** — ByteDance new dev VM, same spec, xiyu.wang@14.103.164.238:2222→192.168.0.131\\n- **A800-dev** — RETIRED Mar 12 2026, replaced by dev-intern-01/02\\n- **A800-1gpu** — 14.103.39.112:17175, RETIRED Mar 11 2026\\n- **NTU Cluster** — 10.97.216.128 (xiyu004), Slurm, A40/A6000/L40/Pro6000/V100, no root\\n  - Project dir: `~/xiyu004var/armesh-dev/` (SSD symlink)\\n  - GLBs: `~/xiyu004general/data/glb/` (18,092 files)\\n  - Blender: `~/xiyu004var/armesh-dev/blender-5.0.1-linux-x64/blender`\\n  - Conda env: `~/xiyu004var/envs/vae-train` (home quota limited, use xiyu004var/ for large files)\\n  - LMOD: `module load Miniforge3/24.11.3-1 CUDA/12.4.0 GCC/13.2.0`\\n  - TRELLIS2: `third_party/trellis2/trellis2/` (copied from MS TRELLIS `trellis/` package)\\n  - Compile: sbatch on cpu-1, never login node. sm_86 for most GPUs.\\n- **L40S** — 10.97.27.230:33803 (xiyu), NTU container, 4×L40S 46GB, 128 CPU, 755GB RAM, 5.1TB NVMe\\n  - Docker, sudo pw `1111`, driver 555.42.06\\n  - Installed: libnvidia-gl-550 + libegl1 for Blender EGL\\n  - Blender 5.0.1 at `~/armesh-dev/blender-5.0.1-linux-x64/`\\n  - Smoke500 at `~/armesh-dev/data/smoke-data/glb/`\\n- **laptop-xiyu** → 100.81.128.1\\n- SSH key: `~/.ssh/id_rsa.1`\\n\\n## Repos\\n- `armesh-dev`: `TimandXiyu/armesh-dev.git`, branch `main` (single branch, cleaned history)\\n  - .git purged from 419MB → 4.5MB (removed third_party assets from history)\\n  - third_party/ (11 repos): plain source snapshots, no .git dirs\\n- `VLMDataClean`: `SparcAI-Inc/VLMDataClean.git` — productionized annotation for company\\n  - Extends armesh-dev attrs: adds texture_quality, is_white_model, is_ai_generated, low_confidence\\n  - Uses nvdiff renders from TOS (vs Blender EEVEE in armesh-dev)\\n- HF dataset: `xiyuwang/armesh-dev` (public), ~9.9k/10.25k GLBs uploaded\\n\\n## 2M Annotation Stream — IN PROGRESS\\n- tmux `annotate` on A800-1gpu, Blender EEVEE → 72B fewshot v2 via vLLM\\n- Script: `tools/annotate_stream.py`, output: `data/qwen-anno-72b-fewshot-v2/`\\n- **STOPPED Mar 11** — A800-1gpu node retired by Tim\\n- ~1.3M JSONs done, ~600k SHAs remaining (unannotated)\\n- vLLM backend (A800-dev) still running\\n- 8 attrs: geometry_quality, is_scan, no_semantic, is_closed_mesh, separated_objects, is_scene, has_clean_topology, is_human\\n- Distribution: Keep ~62%, Borderline <1%, Reject ~37%\\n\\n## Annotation History\\n- 72B zero-shot: 10k, 62.8% accept\\n- 27B zero-shot: 10k, ~51% keep\\n- 72B few-shot v1: 1k, too cautious (39.2% keep, 45.5% borderline)\\n- 72B few-shot v2: 1k, **best** (62.9% keep, 1.5% borderline) — now used for 2M stream\\n\\n## DINOv3 Artisan Classifier\\n- DINOv3-ViTS16 + linear head, 5-fold CV on 10,057 samples\\n- Acc 92.3%, F1 95.5%, Prec 94.2%, Recall 97.0%\\n\\n## AR Mesh Architecture Reference\\n- **VAE**: Michelangelo ShapeVAE-256 (MAv2, BPT, MeshMosaic, FastMesh); EdgeRunner uses DummyLatent; TreeMeshGPT uses perceiver\\n- **Condition**: prefix (MAv2, EdgeRunner, FastMesh) vs true cross-attn (BPT, TreeMeshGPT, MeshMosaic)\\n- **Topology**: only EdgeRunner guarantees manifold (half-edge ops); BPT does merge_vertices post-hoc\\n- **Bottleneck**: attention O(n²), not tokenization. BPT at ~1.5 tok/face ≈ 12 bits/face is near-optimal\\n- **Scaling paths**: sparse attention (HiFi-Mesh LANE) or patch decomposition (MeshMosaic)\\n- **EdgeRunner meto**: Edgebreaker-inspired, L/R/BOM ops + parallelogram residuals, state machine enforced at inference\\n- **MeshCraft**: flow-based DiT, 1 tok/face, max 800-1536 faces, 35× faster than MeshGPT but doesn't scale\\n\\n## Manual Annotation Dataset (artistic_scan_index.json)\\n- 3,735 SHAs from rc_wu's dataset (2,508 artistic / 1,227 scan), different source from 2M\\n- CSV: `data/manual_all_shas.csv`\\n- Clean annotation outputs (dedicated dirs, never mix into main pipeline dirs):\\n  - `data/qwen-manual-72b-fewshotv2` — 72B, fewshot v2 prompt, Blender, completed Mar 10\\n  - `data/qwen-manual-27b-toszero` — 27B SparcAI, TOS zero-shot prompt, Blender, completed Mar 10\\n- 27B TOS distribution: Keep 17%, Border 8%, Reject 75% (scan-heavy)\\n- 72B fewshot distribution: Keep 37%, Border 1%, Reject 61%\\n\\n## 27B TOS Annotation — COMPLETE ✅\\n- `qwen-anno-27b-tos`: 1,911,755 files total\\n- Old file_index.csv (1,766,656) + new gap SHAs (344,776 done, 14 failed, 31 skipped)\\n- Final: Keep 29.7%, Borderline 1.4%, Reject 69.0%\\n- 200W CSV SHA col: `sha256_hash` (index 31), 100% TOS wireframe coverage\\n- Sequential distribution: first 100k rows 56% keep, middle stable ~40-42%, last 300k drops to 23-37%\\n\\n## annotate_stream.py — flags added Mar 10\\n- `--zero-shot`: skip fewshot exemplars\\n- `--disable-thinking`: Qwen3 thinking off (`chat_template_kwargs: {enable_thinking: false}`)\\n- `--max-tokens N`: override 512 default\\n- `--tos-prompt`: use TOS zero-shot system prompt instead of fewshot\\n\\n## Gallery Server (A100)\\n- Port 8765, Tailscale: http://100.123.170.90:8765\\n- Merged server v3: manual labeling + multi-model annotations + search/filters/pagination\\n- Scripts: `tools/gallery_server.py` + `tools/gallery_index.html`\\n- Launch: `setsid python3 tools/gallery_server.py --renders data/blender_renders --annotations data/gallery_labels.json --multi-annotations data/qwen_labels_multi.json --manual-labels data/manual_labels.json --port 8765 --host 0.0.0.0 </dev/null &`\\n- Data: 26,888 SHAs with wireframes, 28,092 VLM annotations, 10k multi-model, 185 manual labels\\n- Images: `wireframe_top_left.jpg` (cropped 1536×1536), `wireframe.webp` (full 4608×3072 grid)\\n\\n## Cluster Blender Renders — IN PROGRESS\\n- 16 jobs (42869-42884 + 42886), V100 + Pro6000 nodes\\n- STEP=1131 per job, skip-existing, --requeue, QoS override-limits-but-killable\\n- 16,151/18,092 done (89%) as of Mar 6 7PM\\n- Output: hybrid.jpg + wireframe.jpg per SHA at 1024×1024\\n\\n## New 200W CSV (from Yufei, 2026-03-09)\\n- File: `/dev_vepfs/xiyu/1.csv` (719MB, 2,003,639 records, 48 columns)\\n- Source: `shared-dev/yufei_data/200W_filtered.csv.tar.gz` from BD CPU instance\\n- Key columns: `scanned_prob`, `aesthetic_score_trellis`, `vertex_num`, `has_uvs`, `caption`, `source`\\n- 83% overlap with old file_index.csv; 336k filtered out, 345k new (mostly unlabeled objaverse)\\n- All SHAs have GLBs in TOS bucket (verified 1000/1000)\\n- Sources: 91.2% empty (objaverse), 5.1% sketchfab_trellis, 3.7% github\\n\\n## Manual Labels (rc_wu)\\n- File: `data/artistic_scan_index.json` — 3,735 records (2,508 artistic/67%, 1,227 scan/33%)\\n- Only 20.8% overlap with our 2M dataset — different data source\\n- Agreement: 27B 53.3% (precision 79%, recall 48%), 72B 56.4%\\n- 27B conservative (misses artistic), 72B permissive (lets scan through)\\n\\n## TOS Bucket Structure\\n- `/all-repacked-3d-data/v1/glb/` — full GLB coverage\\n- `v1/wireframe/` — 6-panel webp grid (partial, used by annotate_tos.py)\\n- `v1/nvdiff/{sha}/` — wireframe.jpg + face_normal.jpg (older, broader coverage)\\n- `v1/multi_view_bpy/{sha}/` — rgb.webp + normal_cam.webp 9216×9216 RGBA (newest, partial)\\n- S3 FUSE: must use parallel reads (32+ threads), sequential causes SSH timeouts\\n\\n## BD Internal Network\\n- dev-intern-01: `192.168.0.134` (gateway: 14.103.164.238:2222, user: xiyu.wang)\\n- dev-intern-02: `192.168.0.131` (gateway: 14.103.164.238:2222, user: xiyu.wang)\\n- Root access: `xiyu.wang#root#192.168.0.134` / `192.168.0.131` (root inside container, not host)\\n- **Both are Kubernetes pods** — nvidia-smi shows host PIDs, trust util% not PID list\\n- Co-tenants: liaoyua+, ruochen+, chunyan+, minglin+\\n- A800-dev: RETIRED Mar 12 2026\\n- BD→A100 transfer: only `ssh 'cat file' > local` works (~1.6 MB/s). SCP/rsync/HF all broken.\\n\\n## VAE Overfit Test Results (Mar 19)\\n- **Tiny data** (64 samples, 1430 faces): lr=1e-4 → 99.8% (BD baseline), lr=1e-3 → 92.7%\\n- **Normal data** (64 samples, 121k faces): lr=1e-3 cosine → 78.2% (A100) / 76.7% (BD) — cross-machine verified\\n- CE+bins v1 architecture works, converges, just needs more steps for large face counts\\n- KL=0 for overfit tests (1e-5 causes oscillation at high accuracy)\\n- overfit_test.py: configurable LR, scheduler, KL weight via env vars\\n\\n## Operational Lessons\\n- **NEVER run `du` or `ls` on large/full FUSE filesystems** (VEPFS, S3 mounts). They hang for hours, block the SSH session, and prevent heartbeats from firing (requests-in-flight). Use `stat -f` for free space, `find -maxdepth 1` for top-level listing, or `wc -l` on known files instead.\\n- Read tmux pane for live annotator stats — don't parse 680k+ JSONs (gets OOM killed)\\n- Alpha-transparent webp → JPG: must alpha_composite onto solid bg first, ffmpeg ignores alpha\\n- Gallery process needs setsid + stdin redirect or it dies when parent shell exits\\n- Pro6000 GPU slower than V100 for Blender renders (CPU-bottleneck with 4 CPUs per GPU slot)\\n- CSV with no header + csv.DictReader = silent 0 results (gallery server bug)\\n- git filter-repo purges blobs but removes origin remote — re-add after\\n- Never cancel cluster jobs without Tim's explicit confirmation\\n- `blender_render_glb.py` was lost during git filter-repo purge — backup found in VLMDataClean xiyu-dataclean-dev branch on A100. Now committed to armesh-dev (`7697460`)\\n- RGBA webp → JPG: must alpha_composite onto white bg (not just .convert(\\\"RGB\\\"))\\n- annotate_tos.py field is `annotation.artisan` (not `verdict`) — different schema than expected\\n- When piping Python to remote SSH, variable shadowing with file handles causes silent failures — use unique handle names or write script to file first\\n- Always verify data SHA overlap when comparing runs across machines — different CSVs have different orderings\\n- flex_gemm autotune cache on VEPFS is shared — concurrent writes from multiple processes corrupt it (race condition)\\n- BD has no GitHub SSH key — use `git bundle` relay via A100 for syncing\\n- Local A100 vae env: `source /home/user/miniconda3/bin/activate vae-train` + PYTHONPATH=`third_party/TRELLIS2:armesh-dev`\\n- BD vae env: `conda run -n vae-poc` + PYTHONPATH=`/dev_vepfs/xiyu/armesh-dev:/dev_vepfs/xiyu/trellis2/..`\\n\\n## OpenClaw Notes\\n- Agent routing: `bindings` array in openclaw.json\\n- Heartbeat: 30m interval, monitoring both annotation pipelines + gallery server\\n- Config: `/home/user/.openclaw/openclaw.json`\\n- Model strategy: Opus for heavy thinking/architecture discussion, cheaper models (MiniMax) for routine monitoring/heartbeats to save tokens\\n\\n## Render Speed Benchmark (L40S, Mar 11 2026)\\n- Results: `memory/render-benchmark.md`\\n- Machine: 4× L40S, Blender 5.0.1 EEVEE, smoke500 (500 GLBs ≤4k faces), 1024×1024\\n- **Subprocess per GLB (old baseline)**: 0.35/s (2834ms/model) — cold-start dominated\\n- **Persistent Blender batch (single process)**: 2.07/s — **5.9× faster**\\n- **Sample count**: 64→16 only 6% improvement; 32 samples is sweet spot\\n- **4× parallel workers (1 GPU each)**: 6.5 models/s effective — near-linear scaling\\n- Production for 2M dataset: persistent batch + 4 workers ≈ 51h on L40S (vs ~330h old)\\n- Scripts: `tools/render_fast_eevee.py` (persistent), `tools/bench_render.sh`\\n\\n## Render Speed Benchmark (L40S, Mar 11 2026)\\n- Full results: `memory/render-benchmark.md`\\n- Persistent Blender process vs subprocess: **5.9× faster** (0.48s vs 2.83s/model)\\n- Sample count (64→16): only 6% improvement — not the bottleneck\\n- 4× parallel GPUs (one per L40S): **6.5 models/s** effective, near-linear scaling\\n- Production: persistent batch + 4 workers → 2M models in ~85h on 4×L40S\\n- Script: `tools/render_fast_eevee.py`, benchmark: `tools/bench_render.sh`\\n\\n## Training Preparation\\n- **EdgeRunner first** for smoke test: training code released, meto tokenizer, manifold output\\n- **Smoke500 dataset**: 500 GLBs ≤4k faces (mean 1427, median 1276), all \\\"keep\\\" by 27B\\n  - HF: `xiyuwang/mesh-dev-382620` → `smoke500/`\\n  - Deployed to all 3 machines under `data/smoke-data/`, md5 verified\\n- Face count distribution: ≤4k: 18%, ≤8k: 29%, ≤40k: 72%\\n- Data budget: 50k min viable, 100-200k competitive v1\\n- For v1: use 27B \\\"keep\\\" (high-confidence, 88% agreement with 72B)\\n\\n## HF Dataset\\n- Repo: `xiyuwang/xiyuwang-armesh-dev-31826` (public, created Mar 18 — old `mesh-dev-382620` deleted)\\n- Old repo `xiyuwang/armesh-dev` deleted by Tim (Mar 10)\\n- Token in `.bashrc` on all 3 machines; A800: `HF_ENDPOINT=https://hf-mirror.com`\\n- NTU cluster: `module load Miniforge3/24.11.3-1 && source activate base`\\n- manual-anno upload in progress (tmux `hf-upload` on A800-1gpu): GLBs + renders + annotations for 3,735 SHAs\\n\\n## Video Annotation (experimental, Mar 10)\\n- 27B SparcAI accepts video input (base64 mp4 via `video_url` type)\\n- ~9× more prompt tokens vs single image (11,959 vs 1,284)\\n- Turntable render: 150 frames too slow (~15 min/model), need single-session Blender script\\n\\n## Cross-Model Agreement (Full, 947k overlap)\\n- Agreement: 67.6% — Both keep 39.1%, Both reject 28.5%\\n\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n31:{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_16\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc 'find /dev_vepfs/rc_wu/zoom-in-render-dino-classfier/sandboxes/20260318_volc_dispatcher_proto -maxdepth 2 -type f | sort'\",\"aggregated_output\":\"/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/zoom-in-render-dino-classfier/sandboxes/20260318_volc_dispatcher_proto/.flex_gemm/autotune_cache.json\\n/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/zoom-in-render-dino-classfier/sandboxes/20260318_volc_dispatcher_proto/PUBLIC_QUEUE_QUICKSTART.md\\n/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/zoom-in-render-dino-classfier/sandboxes/20260318_volc_dispatcher_proto/README.md\\n/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/zoom-in-render-dino-classfier/sandboxes/20260318_volc_dispatcher_proto/__pycache__/controller.cpython-310.pyc\\n/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/zoom-in-render-dino-classfier/sandboxes/20260318_volc_dispatcher_proto/__pycache__/controller.cpython-311.pyc\\n/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/zoom-in-render-dino-classfier/sandboxes/20260318_volc_dispatcher_proto/__pycache__/job_supervisor.cpython-310.pyc\\n/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/zoom-in-render-dino-classfier/sandboxes/20260318_volc_dispatcher_proto/__pycache__/runtime_io.cpython-310.pyc\\n/dev_vepfs/rc_wu/zoom-in-render-dino-classfi